{ No okay, seriously. These are the lines in which I've made wholesale changes to my recommendations. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ Against this popular move, I've recommended a rare but seemingly promising system where White grabs all the space he can, and then tries to develop around it.   3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nd7  5.Nf3  Ngf6  6.Nxf6+   6.Bd3  This was my recommendation last time, following Negi and Collins' advocacy of it. It seems, however, that Rubinstein specialist Georg Meier found a decent way to play against it.  6...c5  7.O-O  Nxe4  8.Bxe4  Nf6  9.Bg5  cxd4  10.Nxd4  Be7  11.Bf3  O-O  12.Qd3  Bc5 !  This was pointed out to me by Chessable user Shufflydoo. Black's position seems to be holding up very well here.  Nxf6  7.Be3 !  A strange-looking move, but I think I dare give it an exclam, at least for now. See the relevant chapter for more details.   3...Nc6  This is the Guimard Variation. I think White has more than one way to get some advantage against this slightly offbeat line, and I decided to present a different way here, leading to less closed positions.  4.Ngf3  Nf6  5.e5  Nd7  6.Bd3  This is my new suggestion. See the 3. ..Nc6 chapter for details.   6.Nb3  was my initial choice, and I still think it's very good. John Shaw has since recommended it in Playing 1.e4: French Defense and Sicilian Sidelines. }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
{ 5.Bd3  is the main move, and what I recommended the first time. I still think it's a really good choice.  5...c5  6.c3  Nc6  7.Ne2  cxd4  8.cxd4  f6  9.exf6  Nxf6  10.Nf3  Bd6  11.O-O  O-O   11...Qc7  12.h3  This still looks like it holds up.  12.Bf4  Bxf4  13.Nxf4  Ne4  14.Ne2  The current opinion seems to be that this Knight retreat is stronger than the alternative 14.Qc1, which I gave in the first course. The exchange sacrifice on f3, which worried me, doesn't seem to give Black full compensation after all, e.g.  14...Rxf3  15.gxf3  Ng5  16.Kh1  e5  17.Qb3  Kh8  18.Bc2  Qf8  19.f4  exf4  20.f3  It is tricky, however. }
5... c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Ngf3
{ Rather than the main move, 7.Ndf3. I think this line is interesting for White, and not that well covered in French Defense literature so far. }
