[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Course Introduction "]
[Black "Let's talk about 3...c5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ I feel comfortable adorning this move with an exclam, because it's almost certainly Black's best move. I think, unless you're one of these Rubinstein guys, if you're a French Defense player, 3...c5 should definitely be the main move in your repertoire. In all the other lines, I feel reasonably confident claiming some sort of an objective advantage. Here, all I can honestly claim is a practical one, in the sense that White's position may be easier to play. I suppose people looking at this from the Black side might disagree with even that claim. 3...c5 is the move that's been "scaring" people toward the main move, 3.Nc3, and I suppose may even be what's causing some people looking for a pragmatic approach to turn to 3.exd5. I don't think the situation is that dire, but of course I have to admit that White doesn't have much objectively. }
4. Ngf3
{ I recommend a slight variance in the move order compared to my first course, but it doesn't make such a big difference.   4.exd5  Qxd5   4...exd5  5.Ngf3  Nc6   5...Nf6   5...a6  is the line I'm avoiding with the 4.Ngf3 move order, although of course there are ways to face this as well.  5.Ngf3  cxd4 }
4... cxd4
{ 4...Nf6  5.exd5  exd5   5...Nxd5  This is an extra option Black gets in this 4.Ngf3 move order. White seems to be able to reach a slightly better endgame.  6.Bb5+  Bd7  7.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  This is a very solid line for Black, and very close to equal objectively, but White should generally be able to put Black under some slight pressure due to his better pawn structure.   4...a6  5.dxc5  Bxc5  6.Bd3  transposes to the 3...a6 variation.   4...Nc6  5.exd5  exd5  6.Bb5  This is an old line, which has experienced a bit of a revival. White should be slightly for choice here, although Black gets quite an active position to compensate for his IQP, and play tends to be very complex. }
5. exd5 Qxd5
{ This is the critical line, wherein Black should be able to achieve a basically equal position in more than one way. I have recommended what I think are the trickiest continuations for Black to face, and the second player does have to know some stuff if he wants to play directly for equality like this. As well, even when Black achieves equality, we don't necessarily have to give up on our ambitions to win the game, of course. }
6. Bc4 Qd6
{ This is the long-standing main line.   6...Qd7 !?  is a newly trendy move, recommended by Tillis & Lenderman on Chessable, and by Edouard on chess24. The move order questions are discussed a little more in depth in the chapters themselves, but essentially Black is trying to put his Queen on a more secure square, so that he can develop more comfortably in a manner of his choosing. The Queen, whether from d6, d7 or d8, tends to end up on c7 regardless. I don't think White should copy the approach from the 6...Qd6 variation, and instead try to play indepedently against Black's move order. The critical line goes as follows:  7.O-O  Nc6  8.Nb3  Nf6  9.Qe2  a6  10.a4  Bd6  11.Rd1  e5  12.Nbxd4  Nxd4  13.Rxd4  Qe7  14.Rxd6  Qxd6  15.b3  when White probably doesn't have enough compensation for the exchange to prove an advantage, but he does certainly have enough to make Black's life difficult.   6...Qd8 !?  tends to be very similar to the above. }
7. O-O Nf6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4
{ Now, Black has three main moves. } 10... a6
{ This has been the main line pretty much since the inception of this variation, as far as I'm aware. It's a good system for Black, but there's a lot to know. Here's a summary of White's various options, just so you don't think your would-be opponents have an easy task in this line.   10...Bd7  Personally, I find this to be the least appealing of the three options. White should be slightly better in this variation. As well, given that Black usually castles long, there's not as much of a problem of Black forcibly equalizing and White not being left with sufficient winning chances.   10...Be7 !  I give this an exclam, because my current opinion is that this is Black's easiest path to equality. This wasn't something I thought two weeks ago, but after checking Giri's Lifetime Repertoire course, I was convinced.  11.c3   11.b3  is Komodo's choice, and looks attractive, but Black seems to be fine after  11...O-O  12.Bb2  Qf4 !  O-O  12.Qf3  Qc7  13.Bb3  a5 !  This is Giri's recommendation, a move I was not previously aware of.  14.a4  Bd7  We'll discuss later on what the inclusion of the moves ...a5 and a4 does for Black, but for now I'll just say that this seems to be Black's most solid choice, and the computer gives me a flat 0.00. It's not quite hopeless for White, but I'm just being honest. }
11. Re1 { 11.Bb3  Qc7  12.Qf3  is also interesting. } 11... Qc7 12. Bf1
{ might be White's best move objectively. It will be my main suggestion in this course. The main line goes as follows:   12.Qe2  is my old recommendation, and Black still seems to have to know  12...h6 !!  and some relevant details in order to equalize.   12.Bd3  is a backup line I suggest, where the most popular continuation may actually be somewhat risky for Black. Realistically, though, if he makes a few accurate moves he's totally fine.   12.Bb3  The old main line.  12...Bd6  13.Nf5   13.h3  O-O  14.Bg5  isn't supposed to be too dangerous, but White can definitely play this way.  Bxh2+  14.Kh1  O-O  15.Nxg7  Rd8  16.Qf3  Kxg7  17.Bh6+  Kg6  is a very sharp line, which both players need to know inside out to enter @@StartBracket@@but we don't have to enter it; however, just the fact that it exists increases Black's workload@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Bd6 { 12...Be7  is characteristically safe and slightly passive. } 13.
Nf5 { 13.g3  is also possible, but shouldn't really be dangerous. } 13... Bxh2+
14. Kh1 Kf8
{ 14...O-O ?!  15.Nxg7 !  is a better version for White of the 12.Bb3 line above. }
15. Qd4 exf5 16. Qxf6 h6 { or   16...h5 !? } 17. Qd4 Bd6 18. Bc4 Be6 19. Bxe6
Re8 20. Qd5 Qe7 21. Qxf5 Qh4+ 22. Kg1 Qh2+ 23. Kf1 Qh1+ 24. Ke2 Rxe6+ 25. Qxe6
Qxe1+ 26. Kxe1 fxe6 27. Be3 { with an ever so slight pull for White. } *

