[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pawn Structures "]
[Black "The Clamp Structure "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. c3
{ This is the pawn structure we're going to explore in the first theoretical chapter. Essentially, White has a large space advantage, which Black tries to put pressure on in various manners. This can involve ...Nc6 and ...Qb6, attacking d4, which White can defend with Nf3, Nb3 and Be3. Black frequently tries ...a7-a5 to annoy a Knight on b3/discourage a Knight from going there. In this case, White often replies with a2-a4, weakening the b4 square and also potentially leaving a Knight somewhat looser on b3. However, Black does also find himself weakening the b5 square in this case, and White is sometimes able to exploit this with Nd2-b1-a3-b5. White's ambitious plans in the long run include f4-f5, as well as capturing on c5 and making a home for a piece  (probably a Knight)  on d4.   In the short term, though, play often revolves around White trying to stabilize his centre. There are variations wherein Black takes on d4 and gives a check from b4. Blocking on d2 blocks the Queen's defense of d4, meaning Kf2 is sometimes required. This is risky, given that it is on the diagonal of a Queen on b6, as well as on the file of a Rook on f8. However, Be3 can limit the danger of the former, and a Knight on f3 tends to keep the King secure along the file, for long enough to whisk it away to g1. White has to make sure Black isn't able to favourably carry out a sequence such as ...c5xd4, c3xd4, ...f6xe5, f4xe5, ...Rf8xf3, followed by taking on d4 and taking on e5, destroying White's centre and getting two pawns for the exchange. We will see an example of this where White manages to more or less consolidate, but it is certainly a dangerous weapon in Black's arsenal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pawn Structures "]
[Black "The Rubinstein Structure "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3
{ This is a pretty broad structure, with many approaches that White can take. I don't want to say that Black's play is one-dimensional, but he does tend to be heavily focused on executing the ...c5 break. If it works, it works. White currently has a space advantage, owing to his pawn on d4. The aforementioned break challenges this advanced pawn, and if he exchanges his c-pawn for White's d-pawn, White no longer has a space advantage, and has to purely rely on a development lead/active pieces/attack. Sometimes this is sufficient, but sometimes Black can gradually equalize, and other times he may just equalize on the spot. After the c-pawn is traded for the d-pawn, Black even has a central majority, and sometimes can contemplate taking over the centre himself with ...e6-e5. To be fair, though, White still has a Queenside majority, and therefore some endgames may be favourable for him.   My aim in this structure, in the lines I present, is to stop Black's ...c5 push, or at least force him to make some small concessions if he wants to execute it. Therefore, I suggest putting the Bishop on e3 very early; not the most obvious square for it, but it does dissuade ...c7-c5. Black may try ...Nd5 to chase the Bishop back, and then play for ...c5, but the Knight being on d5 allows White to set his Queenside pawns in motion very quickly, as c2-c4 comes with tempo. This, combined with Black's King still being in the centre, means that White should have good chances. If Black delays the ...c5 break, White can point to his space advantage as a reason for a small plus for a little bit longer. I suggest setting up with Bd3, Qe2 and 0-0-0, with some potential for a Kingside attack. Black may still try to execute ...c5, but at that point it comes down to the specific position. White may try to increase his space advantage with c2-c4 if he sees fit  (if the Kingside attack isn't working)  , and Be3-g5 can be an annoying pin once Black castles short. There is, of course, the standard opposite sides castling plan of running the g-pawn up the board, although this tends to be more effective when White plays Bg5, and succeeds in provoking ...h7-h6, as a hook for the attack. Black, for his part, tends to set up with ...b6 and ...Bb7, which may re-inforce the ...c5 break. The Dark Squared Bishop may go to either d6 or e7, although the former is slightly more active, and also clogs up the d-file, which, once again, makes ...c5 more likely. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pawn Structures "]
[Black "The "Open" Tarrasch Structure "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ 3...Nc6  4.Ngf3  Nf6  5.e5  Nd7  6.Bd3  Nb4  7.Be2  c5  8.c3  Nc6  9.O-O  cxd4  10.cxd4  f6  11.exf6  Nxf6 }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. Bd3 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Ne2 cxd4 8. cxd4 f6 9. exf6 Nxf6 10. Nf3 Bd6
11. O-O
{ Alright, it's time to talk about the French Tarrasch structure. Well, okay, I'm not sure it's the structure anymore, but it's an important one regardless. This d4 vs. d5/e6 with no c-pawns, no e-pawn for White and no f-pawn for Black, as far as I'm aware, is pretty unique to this opening. Okay, so, what are the advantages for White? Due to the absence of Black's f-pawn, the e5 square and e6 pawn stand out as targets. Therefore, one of White's key plans is to exchange Dark Squared Bishops, both to fight for e5 and to limit Black's potential of a Kingside attack. If Bf4 is prevented, then Bg5-h4-g3 is another way of doing this. The e6 pawn can also find itself coming under threat, for example, with Re1 and Nf4/Ng5. Meanwhile, Black's 'French' Bishop on c8 is still quite 'bad', and it's not unheard of for White to achieve textbook good Knight vs. bad Bishop positions in this structure. Okay, so why does Black ever allow this structure? Well, the simple answer is generally Kingside chances. He's got the half-open f-file, so White definitely has to be on the lookout for sacrifices on f3. He often plays ...Qc7 to prevent Bf4, and create a battery pointing towards f2. The 'bad' French Bishop very often wiggles around to h5; ...Bd7-e8-h5. Objectively speaking, I think White should be doing well strategically, and Black's Kingside play shouldn't quite be sufficient for equality. However, it's tricky.   The good news for us is that we get these positions basically a full tempo up via the 3...Nc6 variation. In that line, Black pretty much gives us the move Bf1-e2 for free, and argues it doesn't matter because the Bishop doesn't belong there anyway. Well, it doesn't, but it's not such a big deal that we'll turn down the chance for a clear tempo gain. White can play Be2-d3 at a moment of his choosing 'giving back the tempo', if he feels this is a big deal, but the Light Squared Bishop sometimes finds itself going to b5 as well, with the intention of eliminating the c6 Knight to try and conquer e5. Note that a Bishop on e2 also dissuades ...Rxf3 sacrifices in general while it's there. All in all, this is a complex structure, where White is strategically better, but Black has his chances. In our version, we tend to be fairly safe, as far as I can tell, and should therefore be able to claim a plus. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pawn Structures "]
[Black "The IQP Structure "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8.
O-O
{ Genuinely, what can I write that hasn't already been written? The IQP is a pawn that has no friendly pawns on neighbouring files, meaning it can only be defended by pieces. This means it can be a target, especially in an endgame, and the square in front on it can be a nice home for a piece. It also gives the side wielding it a space advantage and some attacking chances. The thing is, this structure occurs in a few different versions throughout the 3...c5 variation, and all of them have slightly differing ideas. Therefore, instead of bombarding you with a long-winded, unnecessary and probably incomplete thesis on the IQP, I'll mostly refer you to individual variations, where I'll try to explain the ideas when they come up.   In general, occupying the d4 square with a Knight tends to be a good way to go, often supported by c2-c3 and/or Be3. The d2 Knight usually goes to b3  (although the route Nf1-e3 has been becoming more popular)  , and if it isn't the one that gets to land on d4, c5 is often a destination of interest. The Bishop on b5, if it's not traded for its counterpart @@StartBracket@@i.e. after 4...Nf6 5.exd5 exd5 6.Bb5+ Bd7 7.Bxd7+ Nbxd7, which in theory should benefit White because it's one piece trade closer to an ending, but in practice, it's not so clear@@EndBracket@@ tends to drop back to d3, from where it targets h7 and discourages ...Bf5  (due to the potential piece exchange)  . Playing against the Bishop on c8 is often an idea, wherein White plays h2-h3 and Bb5-d3, to leave it with no particularly ideal squares.   Black, for his part, has a wide range of ideas, which in general can be summed up by trying to make his pieces as active as possible. In this particular position, the King's Knight kind of has to go to e7 to block the potential check along the e-file. This isn't terribly ideal, but not the end of the world. Hence in the aforementioned variation with 4...Nf6, Black allows a piece exchange, in part to faciliate the re-capture on c5 with the Knight, meaning the Dark Squared Bishop can stay on e7, and the King's Knight can go to f6. Again, lots of small changes to the position can alter what either side is trying to do concretely, but the underlying philosophy tends to remain constant. Black is looking for activity to compensate for a potential long-term weakness. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pawn Structures "]
[Black "The "Improved Rubinstein" Structure "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Ngf3 cxd4 6. Bc4 Qd6 7. O-O Nf6 8.
Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4
{ This is one of the more concrete lines in the French Tarrasch, so a lot of this is based on specific moves. However, I did want to make a few general points here. I call this the 'Improved Rubinstein' because this is essentially the Rubinstein structure but where Black has achieved his goal and played ...c5 and exchanged his c-pawn for White's d-pawn. Therefore, he's achieved a central majority, which he may use to start to take over the initiative someday.   White has the Queenside majority, but he shouldn't necessarily be relying on an endgame to achieve something in this variation. It's a bit Sicilian-esque; White should be using his active pieces and lead in development to offset Black's central majority. Some common ideas are Re1 with the idea of Nf5, Bg5 combined with Bd3 or c3/Bb3-c2, targetting h7, as well as g3 and Bf4. This doesn't enumerate all of White's plans, but it's a taste of what his play tends to be like in this line. Black, for his part, tends to play ...Qc7 and ...Bd6, although ...Be7 is also playable, and ...Bd7 with ...0-0-0 is a valid alternative to castling short. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...Nf6"]
[Black "4...Ne4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ Back in 2017 when I was writing 'Fighting the French', I considered this to be Black's most important 3rd move. I was facing it in almost all of my French Tarrasch games, and most people writing books on the French were recommending this line. It makes sense, because it strongly compels White to enter the standard French pawn structure after e4-e5. However, times have changed, and I think they were already starting to change 3 or 4 years ago.  3...c5  is clearly the main line, and 'everybody' seems to be recommending it in their repertoire books, with  3...Nf6  having been left in the dust a little bit. That being said, it's still a totally serious move, and for the sake of variety, and because I think I have an interesting, rare line to present, I'm switching up my recommendation for this course. }
4. e5 Ne4
{ This isn't a very common move, but it leads to an unusual pawn structure, so it's worth briefly checking. Spoiler alert, after the main move  (by far)   4...Nfd7  , I'm going to suggest  5.f4  rather than  5.Bd3  (although I think the latter is still a very good choice) }
5. Nxe4
{ 5.Bd3  is also possible, but this lets Black simplify the position somewhat. The text is an attempt to punish Black's odd 4th move. }
5... dxe4
{ This is a pretty unusual pawn structure. Black's pawn on e4 can potentially be a target, but it also takes away some squares from White's pieces, and if Black can conveniently break with ...c5, he may well just be fine. }
6. Bc4
{ Good move - Black was planning to break with ...c5; now White can answer that with d4-d5. }
6... a6 7. a4 { Stopping counterplay with ...b5. } 7... b6
{ With ...c5 no longer desirable, and ...b5 stopped, Black opts for slower play. However, this isn't really a challenge to the verdict of 'White is better'. }
8. Ne2
{ With f3 not currently available, the Knight heads for the nice square on f4, where it contests the open d5 square.   8.Nh3  should lead to the same thing. }
8... Bb7 9. Nf4 Nc6 10. Be3
{ White has a pleasant position, and an advantage. } *

