[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...Nf6"]
[Black "6...cxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ Back in 2017 when I was writing 'Fighting the French', I considered this to be Black's most important 3rd move. I was facing it in almost all of my French Tarrasch games, and most people writing books on the French were recommending this line. It makes sense, because it strongly compels White to enter the standard French pawn structure after e4-e5. However, times have changed, and I think they were already starting to change 3 or 4 years ago.  3...c5  is clearly the main line, and 'everybody' seems to be recommending it in their repertoire books, with  3...Nf6  having been left in the dust a little bit. That being said, it's still a totally serious move, and for the sake of variety, and because I think I have an interesting, rare line to present, I'm switching up my recommendation for this course. }
4. e5 Nfd7
{ This is Black's main choice by far. From d7, the Knight supports the ...c5 break, and assists in pressuring the e5 pawn. }
5. f4
{ Okay, so here's where I'm deviating from my old course. Again, to reiterate, I still think  5.Bd3  is an excellent move and would highly recommend you play it if the lines I give in this chapter don't appeal to you. Anyway, the philosophy of  5.f4  is pretty simple: we want to grab all the space. }
5... c5 6. c3
{ 6.Ngf3  is also played. You can argue about whether it's a problem that  6...cxd4  forces recapture with the Knight or not. I find it simpler to just cover the  d4  point with the pawn immediately. }
6... cxd4
{ This is recommended by Tillis and Lenderman in their French Defense course. To be entirely honest, I'm not sure what the benefit is of taking on d4 so early. It feels like this allows White a nice maneuver, which we'll see in a moment. }
7. cxd4 Nc6 8. Ngf3
{ Again, this is the Knight development I am suggesting you choose. } 8... a5
{ Black intends to take away the b3 square from White's Knight with ...a5-a4, and just generally expand on the Queenside. Tillis and Lenderman cover the natural  9.a4  , which I suppose is what Black is hoping for, weakening the b4 square significantly. I think White has a better move, and it turns out the Queen's Knight doesn't need b3.     During beta testing, I was asked about the move  8...f5!?  . Black aims to simply block the Kingside and not allow White any dreams of an f4-f5 break anytime soon. Black is effectively conceding a slight disadvantage, as he makes no attempt to challenge White's space edge  (given that ...f7-f6 is no longer on the table)  (, but it would be good to have some idea of how to proceed with White.)     There's nothing wrong with a normal sequence such as  8...f5  9.Be2  Nb6  10.O-O  Be7  11.Nb3  . However, my computer suggests a very interesting and modern-looking plan:  9.h4!?  (this feels AlphaZero-esque)  9...Be7  10.h5  h6  11.Be2  O-O  12.Kf2  (the King is safe here when the centre is closed)  12...Kh8  13.Nf1  Nb6  14.Ne3  (this is a maneuvre which we'll see again)  (when White looks well placed to play on both sides of the board.) }
9. Nb1
{ With the c3 square now open, White swings his Knight there. This is surely not the most natural move, but with White's centre not under immediate pressure, he has time to reorganize his pieces to their ideal squares. This is effectively an 'extra' option, which I think should dissuade Black from taking so early on d4. }
9... a4 10. Nc3 Nb6 11. Bd3 Bd7 12. O-O
{ White has a comfortable position; his centre isn't under any particular pressure at the moment, and he's developed his Kingside and gotten castled in safety. Next is to prepare the f4-f5 push. }
