14. Bb5
{ A nice move, neutralizing any potential danger to e5 by half-pinning both Knights. White's centre remains intact, and Black's Queenside in particular is extremely tied up as a result. The computer already says that White has a winning advantage. Once again, Black's King may turn out to be the more unsafe of the two.   Black has two pawn captures available to him, but neither of them succeed in making White's King uncomfortable,   e.g.  14...gxf4  15.gxf4  fxe5  16.dxe5!  - keeping the f-file closed and also gaining a tempo -  16...Qc7  and now many moves are good, for example  17.Rg1  , with a big advantage. }
