{ This is another retreating move, but in my opinion it has a clearer purpose. Black is intending ...Nb6-c4. }
14. Rf1 Nb6 15. Qc2
{ Hitting  h7  and fighting for the  c4  square.  15.Kg1  is also possible  (as the Queen's absence from b6 means the e5 pawn is safe from being captured for now)  , but  15...Nc4  16.Bc1  somehow feels a bit compliant.  Next, White is likely to play Kg1 and Rac1, consolidating and completing development. Next step would be try to exploit the weakened Kingside  (Black is a bit hard pressed to deal with the threat to h7 in a way that doesn't significantly weaken himself)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...Nf6"]
[Black "7...Qb6 with 12...0-0 3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ Back in 2017 when I was writing 'Fighting the French', I considered this to be Black's most important 3rd move. I was facing it in almost all of my French Tarrasch games, and most people writing books on the French were recommending this line. It makes sense, because it strongly compels White to enter the standard French pawn structure after e4-e5. However, times have changed, and I think they were already starting to change 3 or 4 years ago.  3...c5  is clearly the main line, and 'everybody' seems to be recommending it in their repertoire books, with  3...Nf6  having been left in the dust a little bit. That being said, it's still a totally serious move, and for the sake of variety, and because I think I have an interesting, rare line to present, I'm switching up my recommendation for this course. }
4. e5 Nfd7
{ This is Black's main choice by far. From d7, the Knight supports the ...c5 break, and assists in pressuring the e5 pawn. }
5. f4
{ Okay, so here's where I'm deviating from my old course. Again, to reiterate, I still think  5.Bd3  is an excellent move and would highly recommend you play it if the lines I give in this chapter don't appeal to you. Anyway, the philosophy of  5.f4  is pretty simple: we want to grab all the space. }
5... c5 6. c3
{ 6.Ngf3  is also played. You can argue about whether it's a problem that  6...cxd4  forces recapture with the Knight or not. I find it simpler to just cover the  d4  point with the pawn immediately. }
6... Nc6 7. Ngf3
{ This is the real rare move. Normally, White plays  7.Ndf3  here, with the standard French Tarrasch idea of putting the Knights on  f3  and  e2  . However, I think this simple development of the Knight has a lot going for it. It keeps the Bishop on  f1  unblocked for one  (White usually doesn't have time to get Ndf3, Bd3 and Ne2 all in in this line, so he often plays Ne2 at a moment when it blocks the Light Squared Bishop)  (, and the Knight on d2 can position itself on b3, or even reroute to b1 and then c3 or a3.) }
7... Qb6
{ This is an obvious move, just putting further pressure on d4 in standard French style. }
8. Nb3
{ Naturally, we don't want to take on c5 and voluntarily dismantle our own centre  (while also leaving our King extremely unsafe)  . This move looks awkward, and to some extent it is, but due to White's preponderance of space, it all works out. }
8... cxd4 9. cxd4
{ Taking back with either Knight is also possible, but since Black can also take on d4 at a very early stage, it feels consistent to just recommend taking back with the pawn almost regardless of circumstances. It is nice to be aware that both Knight recaptures are viable as well. }
9... a5
{ Threatening to oust White's Knight with ...a5-a4, winning the d4 pawn. White has a natural reply to this, of course. }
10. a4
{ This does weaken the b4 square, admittedly, but at least White's Knight is more or less stable on b3 for the time being, so the concern of the d4 pawn just falling off the board is temporarily quelled. }
10... Bb4+
{ Quite an annoying check, again, especially when the Bishop knows it won't have to answer to a2-a3 at a later moment. }
11. Kf2
{ White does have to quite careful, given that the natural  11.Bd2  Bxd2+  leaves White a bit stuck for a recapture that doesn't lose material. People have tried  12.Kxd2  , but okay, if we're moving the King anyway, we may as well send it closer to the Kingside. Yes, it's scary to step onto both the a7-g1 diagonal and the f-file, but  Be3  will soon more or less solve the former problem, and White intends to castle by hand as quickly as he can. }
11... f6
{ Naturally, Black tries to rip open the centre while White's King is sitting on f2. The e5 pawn is also currently under threat due to the pin along the a7-g1 diagonal, but White's next move will rectify that, at least temporarily. }
12. Be3 O-O
{ This is a normal move. White would like to complete development and castle by hand whilst maintaining his centre. In general, if Black doesn't do anything drastic, he tends to be able to do this. }
13. Bd3 fxe5 14. fxe5
{ 14.dxe5  is also a decent move, but I think the text does better at limiting Black's counterplay. }
14... Qd8
{ Chessable user InfiniteFlash points out that  14...g5!?  may look like a tempting possibility here. He points out the following variation:  15.h3  - stopping the immediate ...g4; forcing Black to further expose his King if he wants to force that break through -  15...h5  16.Rf1  g4  17.hxg4  hxg4  18.Kg1  gxf3  19.Rxf3  , when Black has won a piece, but his King is far too exposed to be very happy about it. }
15. Rf1 Nb6 16. Kg1
{ With  ...fxe5  and  fxe5  thrown in, White shouldn't even feel the need to stop  16...Nc4  , as  17.Ng5!  is extremely strong. }
*

