11... Ndb8
{ This is Berg's recommendation in Grandmaster Repertoire 16: the French - Volume Three. It seems a bit passive to me, and the engine suggests an interesting idea. }
12. h4
{ Berg only covered  12.Bd3  and  12.Bb5  .  With Black not playing aggressively with ...f7-f6, White sees it fit to begin expanding on the Kingside. Allowing h4-h5 and even h5-h6 is probably not ideal for Black, but... }
12... h5 { ...weakens the g5 square. } 13. Ng5 Bd7 14. Rh3
{ White has a promising position: his Bishops can go to b5/d3/e2 and d2/e3, he can tuck his King away on g1, and in the long run play for g2-g4 and/or f4-f5. Meanwhile, his centre is quite safe for the time being, and Black's only pawn break - ...f7-f6 - probably will just serve to weaken his position. }
