9... Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Kh1 { Stepping off of the a7-g1 diagonal. } 11... f6
12. Na3
{ If White is given time to play Nc2, and subsequently moves such as Rb1 and Be3, he should be better because of his solid space advantage. Therefore, Black should act quickly if he wants to disturb White's build-up. }
12... fxe5 13. fxe5 cxd4 14. cxd4 Rxf3
{ This is a standard sacrifice; Black gets one or two pawns for the exchange, and dismantles White's pawn centre. He has to do it now, as after Na3-c2, d4 is covered and he won't be given the opportunity. }
15. gxf3
{ This is maybe slightly unnatural, but I think it's a good way to recapture, both opening the g-file for the Rook, and allowing for f3-f4 to be played in the future. }
15... Bxa3 { This isn't so good, for a reason which we will see in a second. }
16. bxa3 Qxd4 17. Rb1 Qxe5 18. Bb2
{ Black has gotten two pawns for exchange, but White now gets to start making threats. }
18... Qd6 19. Rg1 { It turns out that White is actually the one attacking! } *

