[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6
{ Back in 2017 when I was writing 'Fighting the French', I considered this to be Black's most important 3rd move. I was facing it in almost all of my French Tarrasch games, and most people writing books on the French were recommending this line. It makes sense, because it strongly compels White to enter the standard French pawn structure after e4-e5. However, times have changed, and I think they were already starting to change 3 or 4 years ago.  3...c5  is clearly the main line, and 'everybody' seems to be recommending it in their repertoire books, with  3...Nf6  having been left in the dust a little bit. That being said, it's still a totally serious move, and for the sake of variety, and because I think I have an interesting, rare line to present, I'm switching up my recommendation for this course. }
4. e5 Nfd7
{ This is Black's main choice by far. From d7, the Knight supports the ...c5 break, and assists in pressuring the e5 pawn. }
5. f4
{ Okay, so here's where I'm deviating from my old course. Again, to reiterate, I still think  5.Bd3  is an excellent move and would highly recommend you play it if the lines I give in this chapter don't appeal to you. Anyway, the philosophy of  5.f4  is pretty simple: we want to grab all the space. }
5... c5 6. c3
{ 6.Ngf3  is also played. You can argue about whether it's a problem that  6...cxd4  forces recapture with the Knight or not. I find it simpler to just cover the  d4  point with the pawn immediately. }
6... Nc6 7. Ngf3
{ This is the real rare move. Normally, White plays  7.Ndf3  here, with the standard French Tarrasch idea of putting the Knights on  f3  and  e2  . However, I think this simple development of the Knight has a lot going for it. It keeps the Bishop on  f1  unblocked for one  (White usually doesn't have time to get Ndf3, Bd3 and Ne2 all in in this line, so he often plays Ne2 at a moment when it blocks the Light Squared Bishop)  (, and the Knight on d2 can position itself on b3, or even reroute to b1 and then c3 or a3.) }
7... a5
{ In my opinion, this is the critical move. Black pre-empts Nb3, and dispenses with ...Qb6 to give White less time to re-organize his pieces. }
8. Be2
{ This isn't the most common move, but I think it might be the best. The problem with the natural  8.a4  is that after  8...cxd4  9.cxd4   I think  9.Nxd4  is slightly stronger, but this takes some of the pressure off of Black's position  9...Bb4  ,  White doesn't have time to organize with Kf2, Nb3, Be3 and Bd3 because Black skipped out on ...Qb6. Time is key to White's position - if he lags too far behind in development, he may just be in big trouble when the centre opens with ...f7-f6. Now, e2 seems like a less ambitious square for the Bishop than d3, and in some ways it is, but on d3 the d4 pawn is left vulnerable. Just because Black hasn't played ...Qb6 yet doesn't mean he never will. White simply wants to get castled and play Kh1, and then he can reposition his pieces once he has developed and consolidated.    8.Be2  is not mentioned by Williams in Attacking Chess: The French. }
8... Qb6
{ Attacking d4, and with Nb3 unavailable, White would appear to be in some trouble. }
9. Nb1
{ This is a very nice move. White 'undevelops', but this Knight is heading for a3, and subsequently c2, or even b5. Meanwhile, the d4 pawn is given secure protection, and he can proceed with 0-0 and Kh1 next. This re-organizing move is not mentioned by Watson in Play the French 4th Edition. }
9... Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Kh1 { Stepping off of the a7-g1 diagonal. } 11... f6
12. Na3
{ If White is given time to play Nc2, and subsequently moves such as Rb1 and Be3, he should be better because of his solid space advantage. Therefore, Black should act quickly if he wants to disturb White's build-up. }
12... fxe5 13. fxe5 cxd4 14. cxd4 Rxf3
{ This is a standard sacrifice; Black gets one or two pawns for the exchange, and dismantles White's pawn centre. He has to do it now, as after Na3-c2, d4 is covered and he won't be given the opportunity. }
15. gxf3
{ This is maybe slightly unnatural, but I think it's a good way to recapture, both opening the g-file for the Rook, and allowing for f3-f4 to be played in the future. }
15... Nxd4 16. Be3 Bc5 17. Rc1 { Threatening Rxc5 followed by taking on d4. }
17... Qxb2
{ Now, White's Knight is hanging on a3, so that sort of trickery doesn't work. }
18. Bxd4 Qxd4 19. Nb5 Qxd1 20. Rfxd1
{ The important point is that Black can't take on e5, as his Bishop on c5 would hang, therefore, White gets time to solidify his centre. }
20... Kf7 21. f4
{ Black has two pawns for the exchange, yes, but White has managed to maintain the remnants of his centre, and Black's Queenside still has yet to develop, while White's pieces are a picture of activity.     There are a couple of key things to note here. As Chessable user Archer66 points out, it is very important that  21...Be3  can be met by  22.Rxc8!  , winning a piece.   Secondly, Chessable user pd159 brought up the importance of Black's ...g5 break. If  21...g5  immediately, White can play  22.f5  , with the point that  22...Nxe5  would allow  23.Rxc5  .   Instead, if Black starts with  21...b6  , one option is  22.Nd6+  , but probably the best is  22.h4!  , stopping Black's plans of breaking up the White centre. }
