[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...Nf6"]
[Black "7...a5 4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Ngf3 a5 8. Be2
Qb6 9. Nb1 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Kh1 f6 12. Na3 fxe5 13. fxe5 cxd4 14. cxd4 Rxf3
15. gxf3 Qxd4 16. Nb5 Qxd1 17. Rxd1 Ndxe5
{ On the surface, this looks like it might just be fine for Black. The second player has two pawns, two connected, unopposed central pawns at that, for the exchange. However, White has just enough time to break up Black's centre and secure a slightly better position. }
18. f4 Ng6 19. Nc7 Rb8 20. f5
{ An important move, breaking up Black's nice e6/d5 conglomerate and allowing White's pieces some activity. }
20... exf5 21. Nxd5
{ Of course, this is far from easy to convert into a win, but White should have the slightly better chances in this ending, with the position open for his Rooks and Black's pieces on the Queenside still somewhat awkward. }
