1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Ngf3 f6
{ This break is a common feature in the French Tarrasch with 3...Nf6. Somehow, it feels a bit less logical here, with e5 so well defended. Nonetheless, it must at least be a sensible move. }
8. Nb3
{ This is our typical move, clearing the way for the c1 Bishop to develop, and covering d4. }
8... cxd4
{ 8...c4  9.Nbd2  allows Black to get this structure without his Queen on b6, meaning ...b5 can be played more quickly. However, having played ...f6 is not necessarily fantastic for him in this ...c4 structure, as the Kingside is the side of the board that White tends to want to open. exf6 followed by Ne5 @@StartBracket@@if Black recaptures with a piece@@EndBracket@@ may be a very serious consideration.   8...Be7  9.exf6  This is a novelty in this specific position, and perhaps slightly surprising after building up this nice centre. The point is that Black lacks an ideal recapture, as grabbing with a piece would allow White to take on c5.  9...gxf6  10.Nh4  O-O  11.f5±  with nice attacking chances for White. }
9. Nfxd4
{ 9.cxd4  isn't bad, but the text looks like the right way to exploit Black's move order, given that e6 is loose. }
9... Nc5 10. Be3
{ White threatens to take on c6 and take on c5, and it's somewhat awkward for Black to meet it. One sample continuation is: }
10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Ne4
{ 11...Nxb3?!  gives White a completely free hand.  12.axb3  +-  and next comes Bd3, threatening Qh5+. Castling Kingside will hardly get Black out of the line of fire either, as the threats toward h7 will commence. }
12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Bd3 Bd6 14. Qe2
{ White is developed beautifully, and can castle on either side, and begin to put pressure on Black's backward e6 pawn. Bb5+ @@StartBracket@@...Bd7, Qxe6+@@EndBracket@@ may come into the picture as well. }
