1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ This is the most solid line at Black's disposal. The second player relinquishes control of the centre in return for an exceptionally resilient position with no weaknesses. White has to be very precise to keep any advantage at all. }
4. Nxe4 Nf6
{ This is a move I initially didn't cover in the original repertoire. In terms of frequency, it's a distant third behind  4...Nd7  and  4...Bd7  , but I have actually faced it in a tournament game, so including it makes sense. }
5. Nxf6+
{ The problem is that Black doesn't really have an ideal recapture on f6 - this is why more often than not Black plays ...Nd7 before ...N  (g)  f6. }
5... Qxf6
{ This is one option, and the move my opponent chose. That being said, it's somewhat less challenging, at least practically speaking -in my opinion - than  5...gxf6  . }
6. Nf3
{ Now Black has to waste time with ...h6 to avoid Bd3 and Bg5, trapping the Queen. }
6... h6 7. Bd3 c5 8. Be3
{ This is how my game from January of 2017 went. White is somewhat better because of his development lead, and Black's slightly misplaced Queen. }
