1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ This is the most solid line at Black's disposal. The second player relinquishes control of the centre in return for an exceptionally resilient position with no weaknesses. White has to be very precise to keep any advantage at all. }
4. Nxe4 Nf6
{ This is a move I initially didn't cover in the original repertoire. In terms of frequency, it's a distant third behind  4...Nd7  and  4...Bd7  , but I have actually faced it in a tournament game, so including it makes sense. }
5. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ Hoping for counterplay down the g-file; combined with Bishops on b7 and d6, this could lead to a rather dangerous Kingside attack. Fortunately, White can neutralize both of these Bishops. }
6. Nf3 b6 7. Bb5+
{ Good move; White compels Black to block the long diagonal. } 7... c6 8. Bd3
Bb7 9. Bf4
{ Another important move - neutralizing the King's Bishop's future diagonal. }
9... Bd6 10. Bg3
{ Good move - as pointed out by Tzermiadianos, after ...Bxg3, hxg3, any counterplay on the g-file will be mostly shut down. White emerges with an advantage due to his space advantage and better structure  (h7 and f6 could be weak in the long-term) }
