1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ This is the most solid line at Black's disposal. The second player relinquishes control of the centre in return for an exceptionally resilient position with no weaknesses. White has to be very precise to keep any advantage at all. }
4. Nxe4 Bd7
{ Black maneuvers his Bishop to c6. This is known as the Fort Knox Variation, for its solidity. }
5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nf6
{ This move should once again be prefaced by  6...Nd7  . } 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ This falls for a trap. Instead,  7...gxf6  is necessary, but this is obviously not a particuarly pleasant move to make. }
8. Bg5 { Black's Queen is trapped? No wait, he just has... } 8... Bxf3
{ Ah, hang on, but... } 9. Qd2
{ ...it's trapped anyways. This is a very nice line which I've gotten in internet blitz games several times, and even once in a serious game Over The Board. }
