1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ This is the most solid line at Black's disposal. The second player relinquishes control of the centre in return for an exceptionally resilient position with no weaknesses. White has to be very precise to keep any advantage at all. }
4. Nxe4 Bd7
{ Black maneuvers his Bishop to c6. This is known as the Fort Knox Variation, for its solidity. }
5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Ng3
{ White, with more space, should avoid exchanges on principle. I'll just give two examples of how play can continue from here. There are no forced lines you have to know, and White has a pleasant position with natural moves. }
8... Be7 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 Bxf3
{ Seeking to exchange a set of pieces and solidify his pawn structure with ...c6. Of course, this comes at the cost of the Bishop pair. }
11. Qxf3 c6 12. c4
{ There isn't much to know here. White simply has a very pleasant position with the Bishop pair. He can follow up with, for instance, Rad1 and Rfe1, tuck the Bishop away on b1, then, with all of his pieces beautifully placed, look for attacking chances. }
