1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ This is the most solid line at Black's disposal. The second player relinquishes control of the centre in return for an exceptionally resilient position with no weaknesses. White has to be very precise to keep any advantage at all. }
4. Nxe4 Bd7
{ Black maneuvers his Bishop to c6. This is known as the Fort Knox Variation, for its solidity. }
5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Ng3 g6
{ This move has become a bit trendy lately, inasmuch as anything in the Fort Knox is trendy. I didn't cover it in my first course, but there's really only one detail you should keep in mind: }
9. b3
{ Starting with  9.c4  is also logical, but there's actually a good reason to begin by playing this move. }
9... Bg7 10. Ba3
{ ...and this is it. By preventing castling, White basically gains a free tempo. }
10... Bf8 11. Bb2 Bg7 12. c4
{ White has the usual Fort Knox slight advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...dxe4"]
[Black "4...Nd7 with 7...Nd5 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ This is the most solid line at Black's disposal. The second player relinquishes control of the centre in return for an exceptionally resilient position with no weaknesses. White has to be very precise to keep any advantage at all. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ The most popular  (and likely the best)  move. Black prepares to develop his King's Knight to f6, without needing to expose his Queen or double his pawns. Black isn't really aiming for anything terribly ambitious out of the opening, but his moves are very solid, and if White isn't careful, his small advantage could easily turn into nothing. }
5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+
{ I previously recommended  6.Bd3  , this is my new suggestion. } 6... Nxf6 7.
Be3
{ This is a move that has been played a decent amount at the top level, but I'm not sure that it's fully caught on as a main line. That being said, after spending a lot of time looking at moves like  7.c3  , I eventually got tired of Black just pushing  ...c5  and gradually equalizing. Therefore, I eventually settled on this slightly unnatural developing move to stop that break, at least for the time being. This move is not mentioned in Tillis & Lenderman's Master the French Rubinstein French coverage. }
7... Nd5
{ This is a natural way to try to exploit White's last move, but after retreating the Bishop, White can gain a tempo with the subsequent c2-c4. }
8. Bd2 c5
{ I assume this is the point of Black's last, chasing the Bishop away to get the key break in. }
9. Bb5+
{ This is a nice move -  9.c4  Nf6  seems okay for Black.  The point is twofold; by exchanging Light Squared Bishops, White gets rid of a piece that may not have had a clear role, and also importantly lures Black's Queen to d7, where it can be hit by Ne5. }
9... Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. c4 Nb6
{ The other retreat,  11...Nf6  , can be met by a similar idea;  12.Ne5  followed by Qa4+. }
12. Rc1 { Covering c4. Meanwhile, Black shouldn't really be taking on d4... }
12... cxd4 13. c5 Nd5 14. Ne5 Qc7 15. Qa4+
{ White not only forces Black's King to move, but he also picks up his pawn back on d4. }
*

