1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ This is the most solid line at Black's disposal. The second player relinquishes control of the centre in return for an exceptionally resilient position with no weaknesses. White has to be very precise to keep any advantage at all. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ The most popular @@StartBracket@@and likely the best@@EndBracket@@ move. Black prepares to develop his King's Knight to f6, without needing to expose his Queen or double his pawns. Black isn't really aiming for anything terribly ambitious out of the opening, but his moves are very solid, and if White isn't careful, his small advantage could easily turn into nothing. }
5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+
{ I previously recommended  6.Bd3  , this is my new suggestion. } 6... Nxf6 7.
Be3
{ This is a move that has been played a decent amount at the top level, but I'm not sure that it's fully caught on as a main line. That being said, after spending a lot of time looking at moves like  7.c3  , I eventually got tired of Black just pushing  ...c5  and gradually equalizing. Therefore, I eventually settled on this slightly unnatural developing move to stop that break, at least for the time being. This move is not mentioned in Tillis & Lenderman's Master the French Rubinstein French coverage. }
7... Bd6
{ I think this is probably the critical move. One very compelling argument for that statement is that reknowned Rubinstein expert Georg Meier generally chooses this move against the Be3 line. Given that White has succeeded in temporarily halting the ...c5 break, he can develop as normal, with a long castling plan being the most ambitious. }
8. Bd3 O-O 9. Qe2 b6 10. O-O-O Bb7 11. Bg5
{ Moving this Bishop again doesn't feel obvious, but this pin is quite annoying, and Black often feels the need to resort to ...Be7, giving the tempo back to break it. This retreat also hops off the d-file, meaning that ...c5 is once again inhibited. }
11... c5 { This is just a blunder. } 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qd3+
{ ...and White wins a pawn. } *

