1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ This is the most solid line at Black's disposal. The second player relinquishes control of the centre in return for an exceptionally resilient position with no weaknesses. White has to be very precise to keep any advantage at all. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+
{ I previously recommended  6.Bd3  . This is my new suggestion. } 6... Nxf6 7.
Be3
{ This is a move that has been played a decent amount at the top level, but I'm not sure that it's fully caught on as a main line. That being said, after spending a lot of time looking at moves like  7.c3  , I eventually got tired of Black just pushing  ...c5  and gradually equalizing. Therefore, I eventually settled on this slightly unnatural developing move to stop that break, at least for the time being. }
7... Bd6
{ I think this is probably the critical move. One very compelling argument for that statement is that reknowned Rubinstein expert Georg Meier generally chooses this move against the Be3 line. Given that White has succeeded in temporarily halting the ...c5 break, he can develop as normal, with a long castling plan being the most ambitious. }
8. Bd3 b6
{ Black prepares to fianchetto his Bishop and helps support a future ...c5 break. This can transpose to previous lines if Black follows up with short castling, but he doesn't have to. }
9. Qe2 Bb7 10. O-O-O Qe7
{ 10...O-O  would transpose to previous variations. The text is Langrock's recommendation in French Defense: The Solid Rubinstein Variation. Black remains flexible regarding which side he wants to castle on. }
11. Kb1
{ White, in return, remains flexible. Langrock analyzes  11.Ne5  , which can be met by  11...O-O-O  ,   and  11.Bb5+  c6  12.Ba6  , whereupon Black can switch back to the plan of castling short.   Instead, the computer suggests a waiting move in reply, which is generally useful, and patiently waits for Black to decide where his King is going. If  11.Kb1  O-O-O  , then after a move such as  12.Rhe1  ,  White is better, because the second player putting his King on the Queenside makes the ...c7-c5 break, one of Black's main sources of counterplay, significantly riskier. Meanwhile,  11.Kb1  O-O  12.Bg5  looks good for White, as the Queen being on  e7  means that Black cannot easily break the pin with  ...Be7  , as we've seen before. }
