[White "3...dxe4"]
[Black "5...Be7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
{ This is the most solid line at Black's disposal. The second player relinquishes control of the centre in return for an exceptionally resilient position with no weaknesses. White has to be very precise to keep any advantage at all. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ The most popular @@StartBracket@@and likely the best@@EndBracket@@ move. Black prepares to develop his King's Knight to f6, without needing to expose his Queen or double his pawns. Black isn't really aiming for anything terribly ambitious out of the opening, but his moves are very solid, and if White isn't careful, his small advantage could easily turn into nothing. }
5. Nf3 Be7
{ This is a slightly unusual move order. I think the idea is that Black is trying to bypass certain lines by introducing the option of meeting ...Ngf6, Nxf6+ with ...Bxf6, which may or may not serve as preparation for ...e5. It is a bit passive, however, and ...Be7 is not always necessarily the first priority for Black. }
6. Be3
{ Okay, I'll admit this is a really funny looking move, but it's in line with my main Rubinstein suggestion, and is likely to transpose to it. }
6... Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ Bxf6
{ 7...Nxf6  would transpose to the line  5...Ngf6  6.Nxf6  Nxf6  7.Be3  Be7  . This is an independent line which doesn't really get played much. }
8. Qd3
{ Lots of moves are possible, but somehow this weird-looking one appeals to me. A natural thing to play would be  8.Bd3  , but after  8...c5  , Black seems more or less fine, as the d-pawn is half-pinned to  b2  .     White now intends to meet  8.Qd3  c5  with  9.O-O-O  , with nice pressure along the d-file,   and  8.Qd3  O-O  perhaps with something like  9.h4  , with attacking chances.   Additionally, the aforementioned  8.Qd3  e5  runs into  9.dxe5  Bxe5   9...Nxe5?  10.Nxe5  Bxe5  11.Qb5+!  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Qxd8+  Kxd8  12.O-O-O+  , with a huge initiative that the computer actually considers to be winning. }
