[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...Nc6"]
[Black "6...f6 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nc6
{ Black forgoes the usual ...c5 break for now. His alternative ambitions include breaking with ...e5, and, should White play e4-e5 at some point, breaking with ...f6. This is a line I've struggled against in blitz; Black often gets easy positions when White can't remember what he's meant to do. }
4. Ngf3
{ I think this is the only challenging move. Why not develop and cover the  d4  pawn?  4.c3  would be a nice move to play, preserving the flexibility of the King's Knight  (White could still set up with Bd3, Ne2 and Ndf3)  , but unfortunately  4...e5!  throws a wrench in those plans and should pretty much equalize. }
4... Nf6 5. e5 Nd7 6. Bd3
{ My original repertoire gave  6.Nb3  instead. I still think that move is perfectly good, and in fact was also recommended by John Shaw and the Quality Chess team in Playing 1.e4: French Defense and Sicilian Sidelines. I decided to mix it up for this edition, and I also do actually have some experience with this move from a while ago. It's surely the most natural move in the position at the outset, but hasn't been all that popular overall. }
6... f6
{ This is Black's natural pawn break; in the French in general but especially in the Guimard Variation. It is a bit risky in this particular position, however, as White's Bishop being actively placed on d3, among other things, affords him the possibility for an interesting piece sacrifice. }
7. Ng5
{ Obviously White is intending  Qh5+  , and Black has to be careful to not lose immediately. Incidentally, the calmer  7.exf6  is also quite strong. }
7... fxg5
{ This is the wrong way to do it. With the d7 square unavailable for the King, Black is simply in big trouble. }
8. Qh5+ g6
{ After  8...Ke7  , White doesn't need to do anything special;  9.Nb3  h6  10.O-O  and Black is about to be torn limb from limb with f2-f4. Black lacks a way to untangle his position without sacrificing a piece back, as  ...Qe8  is met with  Bg6  . }
9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Ne4
{ ...and  Black just doesn't really have a good answer to  Bxg5+  , e.g.   
11...Bh6  12.Bxg5+  Bxg5  13.Qg7+  or  11...Ndxe5  12.dxe5  , when  12...Nxe5  loses to  13.Qf6+  , and as Chessable user Bechster pointed out,  11...Ndxe5  12.dxe5  Kd7  must be met by  13.Nf6+  , which wins. }
*

