4... Nf6 5. e5 Nd7 6. Bd3
{ My original repertoire gave   6.Nb3  instead. I still think that move is perfectly good, and in fact was also recommended by John Shaw and the Quality Chess team in Playing 1.e4: French Defense and Sicilian Sidelines. I decided to mix it up for this edition, and I also do actually have some experience with this move from a while ago. It's surely the most natural move in the position at the outset, but hasn't been all that popular overall. }
