{ This is necessary, to clear the d7 square for the King in preparation for White playing Qh5+. It does involve giving up a piece in exchange for the one he's about to capture on g5, but he does at least usually get to keep an extra pawn for his troubles. }
8. dxe5 fxg5 9. Qh5+ Kd7 10. Nf3
{ Covering the e5 pawn, and getting ready to take on g5. } 10... Nb4
{ This was shown by Dmitry Krayvkin in his very recent book, The Modern French, but there is a strong novelty coming soon! }
11. Bxg5
{ White has won the pawn back and should be better. Black can take on d3 with check, grabbing the Bishop pair, but I think White is still for choice due to his development lead and Black's very awkward King situation. }
11... Nxd3+ 12. cxd3 Qe8 13. Qh4 Qg6 14. Qa4+ c6
{ Chessable user Darkestnight has very graciously checked my repertoire against the recent book The Modern French: Volume 2 by Dmitry Kryvakin. Not only that, but he found an improvement on his coverage and provided some notes. The following commentary is mostly his, with some minor adjustments. }
15. Ke2
{ This looks pretty senseless at first, but White's philosophy is not to sacrifice the pawn, and instead to keep the king in the centre and fight on the queenside. The king is very safe in the middle as all Black's pieces are really doing nothing, and there is just no way to attack our majesty! This reminds me of Kramnik's new chess variant, No-Castling Chess :@@EndBracket@@ Also, a point to be noted, this is a novelty and an improvement which was not covered by Dmitry in his new French book!   15.O-O  is a pawn sacrifice, which leads to very unclear play.  15...Qxd3  16.Rfd1  Qg6  17.Rac1  here, there was a game, V.Kovalev - Stupak, K Minsk 2018. But as pointed out by Dmitry Kryavkin in his very recent book, The Modern French: Volume 2,  17...a5 !?  18.Nd4  Ra6  19.Be3  Be7  20.Nb3  Ke8  21.Nc5  Ra8  22.b4  Rf8  23.bxa5  Qh5  24.Bd4  Kf7  25.Qb4  Kg8  ∞  It is indeed unclear, as White's pawns on e5 and a5 are weak, while Black has powerful bishop-pair and a quite acceptable position.   15.Ke2  N  It is very hard to find any good plans for Black. The best I could find was along the lines of:  15...Kc7  16.Rhc1  Bd7  17.b4  b6  18.Qa6 !  Bxb4  19.Rab1  Here, beside the computer move 19. ..Rhf8 Black only has one move to fight for the survival. The bishop does not have a proper square to move, e.g. a move like 19...Bf8 would be a fatal error as after 20.Rxb6 Black is already busted!  19...h6   19...Rhf8  This is a very computer-ish idea, which at first looks simply losing, but it sets up a trick, which you should be aware of!  20.Rxb4  Rxf3  The point! Now White should play the precise move, not allowing any single counterplay:  21.h4 !  The most natural,   21.Kxf3 ?  in order to keep the structure intact and also get the exchange, might even backfire, after  21...Qxg5  with threats on e5 and c1 almost forces White to play  22.Rf4  Qxe5  =+  The position can be even horrible for White, and is of course something to avoid!   21.gxf3  will most probably end in a perpetual after the almost forced sequence  21...Qxg5  22.f4  Qg4+  23.Kd2  Qf3  24.Ke1  Qh1+  25.Kd2 =  21...Rf5  □  again, almost forced. Black must play a bit tenaciously to not to lose. But if White knows what to do, then everything is more than fine!   21...Rff8  with the idea of protecting the rook to prevent ... Rxb6 ideas, fails to  22.Be7  The bishop invades with a disaster for Black!   21...Rf7  22.Rxb6  +-  22.Kf1  ±  The last precise move, and White scratches a simple, solid and better position. 22.Rxb6 should be avoided, that allows unnecessary counterplay, whereas after the text move, White simply prevents the threat of ...Rxe5+ by tactical means, and secures a safe advantage!  20.Bh4 !  Still controlling the e7 square so that the bishop is unable to return. White is simply better, Black will sooner or later have to move his bishop to a5, so let's say he does it this move  20...Ba5  21.Kf1 !  Simple chess, just protecting the g2-pawn, and the threat of Be7-d6 is hard to meet for Black. Note that the move  21...Bc8 ?  intending to trap the queen does not work because of the simple but nice tactics  22.Rxc6+ !  Kxc6  23.Rc1+  Kd7  24.Qb5  a nice example of Boden's mate! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...Nc6"]
[Black "6...Nb4 with 9...Be7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nc6
{ Black forgoes the usual ...c5 break for now. His alternative ambitions include breaking with ...e5, and, should White play e4-e5 at some point, breaking with ...f6. This is a line I've struggled against in blitz; Black often gets easy positions when White can't remember what he's meant to do. }
4. Ngf3
{ I think this is the only challenging move. Why not develop and cover the  d4  pawn?  4.c3  would be a nice move to play, preserving the flexibility of the King's Knight  (White could still set up with Bd3, Ne2 and Ndf3)  , but unfortunately  4...e5!  throws a wrench in those plans and should pretty much equalize. }
4... Nf6 5. e5 Nd7 6. Bd3
{ My original repertoire gave  6.Nb3  instead. I still think that move is perfectly good, and in fact was also recommended by John Shaw and the Quality Chess team in Playing 1.e4: French Defense and Sicilian Sidelines. I decided to mix it up for this edition, and I also do actually have some experience with this move from a while ago. It's surely the most natural move in the position at the outset, but hasn't been all that popular overall. }
6... Nb4
{ I suppose this is the argument against playing White's sixth move. By 'gaining a tempo' on the Bishop, Black gets time to clear his c-pawn in order to execute the thematic ...c5 break. That being said, White is playing Bd3-e2, and Black is playing ...Nb4-c6  @@StartBracket@@after it's kicked by c3@@EndBracket@@. This amounts to a gain of a tempo for White, albeit the somewhat timid looking Be2. That being said, a tempo is a tempo. }
7. Be2 c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. O-O
{ I remember I used to like the idea of playing  9.Bd3  here, voluntarily giving back the tempo to improve the Bishop.  That's because I used to play the line 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4.e5 Nfd7 5.Bd3 c5 6.c3 Nc6 7.Ngf3, to which that would transpose. It's a nice transposition to be aware of if you happen to play that line. I'm not suggesting it for this repertoire, and I suppose also in a hypertheoretical sense allowing that transposition is more than Black 'deserves' after playing what's supposed to be a slightly dubious variation in 3...Nc6. }
9... Be7
{ This is a slightly passive development, which doesn't do much to challenge White's space advantage. }
10. Re1
{ Remaining flexible; this move serves the dual purpose of clearing f1 for the Knight to route to g3 should the centre remain closed, and also occupying the potentially half open e-file should Black choose to break with ...f6. }
10... O-O 11. Bd3
{ White improves his Bishop, giving back the tempo gained, but transposing into Ngf3 Tarrasch lines where Black has played ...Be7 and ...0-0, meant to be fairly unchallenging. One of White's major plans is Nf1-g3, perhaps followed by Bc2 and Qd3, with a Kingside attack on the horizon. }
