7. Be2 c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. O-O
{ I remember I used to like the idea of playing  9.Bd3  here, voluntarily giving back the tempo to improve the Bishop.  That's because I used to play the line 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4.e5 Nfd7 5.Bd3 c5 6.c3 Nc6 7.Ngf3, to which that would transpose. It's a nice transposition to be aware of if you happen to play that line. I'm not suggesting it for this repertoire, and I suppose also in a hypertheoretical sense allowing that transposition is more than Black 'deserves' after playing what's supposed to be a slightly dubious variation in 3...Nc6. }
9... f6
{ It seems to be better to throw in ...cxd4 before playing this move, for the reason that White seems to be able to profitably make use of the fact that his c-pawn is still on the board. }
10. exf6 Nxf6 11. Re1
{ This is a nice improving move, as the e-file will be an excellent home for the Rook, playing against the potential weaknesses on both e6 and e5. }
11... Bd6 12. dxc5
{ This is a surprising move @@StartBracket@@at least to me@@EndBracket@@, giving up the centre, but White can fully justify it based on the follow-up he has planned: }
12... Bxc5 13. Nb3 Bd6 14. c4
{ This is a nice follow up, essentially ensuring the splitting of Black's nice 2-on-0 central majority, as he is not presently prepared to play ...d5-d4. Black will end up with an isolated pawn, probably on d5, which White can play against with moves like Be3 and Nbd4. }
