[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nc6
{ Black forgoes the usual ...c5 break for now. His alternative ambitions include breaking with ...e5, and, should White play e4-e5 at some point, breaking with ...f6. This is a line I've struggled against in blitz; Black often gets easy positions when White can't remember what he's meant to do. }
4. Ngf3
{ I think this is the only challenging move. Why not develop and cover the  d4  pawn?  4.c3  would be a nice move to play, preserving the flexibility of the King's Knight  (White could still set up with Bd3, Ne2 and Ndf3)  , but unfortunately  4...e5!  throws a wrench in those plans and should pretty much equalize. }
4... Nf6 5. e5 Nd7 6. Bd3
{ My original repertoire gave  6.Nb3  instead. I still think that move is perfectly good, and in fact was also recommended by John Shaw and the Quality Chess team in Playing 1.e4: French Defense and Sicilian Sidelines. I decided to mix it up for this edition, and I also do actually have some experience with this move from a while ago. It's surely the most natural move in the position at the outset, but hasn't been all that popular overall. }
6... Nb4
{ I suppose this is the argument against playing White's sixth move. By 'gaining a tempo' on the Bishop, Black gets time to clear his c-pawn in order to execute the thematic ...c5 break. That being said, White is playing Bd3-e2, and Black is playing ...Nb4-c6  @@StartBracket@@after it's kicked by c3@@EndBracket@@. This amounts to a gain of a tempo for White, albeit the somewhat timid looking Be2. That being said, a tempo is a tempo. }
7. Be2 c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. O-O
{ I remember I used to like the idea of playing  9.Bd3  here, voluntarily giving back the tempo to improve the Bishop.  That's because I used to play the line 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4.e5 Nfd7 5.Bd3 c5 6.c3 Nc6 7.Ngf3, to which that would transpose. It's a nice transposition to be aware of if you happen to play that line. I'm not suggesting it for this repertoire, and I suppose also in a hypertheoretical sense allowing that transposition is more than Black 'deserves' after playing what's supposed to be a slightly dubious variation in 3...Nc6. }
9... a5 10. a4 Be7 11. Nb1
{ The Knight is hopping around to the newly weakened b5 square. Incidentally, if you recall the 3...Nf6 chapter, this isn't the first time we've seen this maneuver. }
11... O-O 12. Na3 cxd4 13. cxd4 f6 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Nb5 Bd7 16. Bd3
{ This is a structure typical of the French Tarrasch, but White has a better version than he normally would. Black's Bishop would like to be on d6, fighting for the key e5 square, but our wonderful Knight on b5 is currently impeding this. White will likely follow up with Re1, with excellent chances to play against the e5 square and the e6 pawn. }
