7. Be2 c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. O-O
{ I remember I used to like the idea of playing  9.Bd3  here, voluntarily giving back the tempo to improve the Bishop.  That's because I used to play the line 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4.e5 Nfd7 5.Bd3 c5 6.c3 Nc6 7.Ngf3, to which that would transpose. It's a nice transposition to be aware of if you happen to play that line. I'm not suggesting it for this repertoire, and I suppose also in a hypertheoretical sense allowing that transposition is more than Black 'deserves' after playing what's supposed to be a slightly dubious variation in 3...Nc6. }
9... cxd4 10. cxd4 f6
{ The standard French break, but I think White is reasonably well placed to meet it. If he doesn't play this soon, however, the second player may find himself struggling for counterplay in a slightly cramped position. }
11. exf6 Qxf6 12. Nb3 Bd6 13. Bg5 Qf7 14. Bh4
{ A standard theme in the French Tarrasch; White swings his Bishop around to g3 in an attempt to trade off Dark Squared Bishops and fight for the key e5 square. Ng5 with tempo may also come into effect at some point. Black retains his 'bad' French Bishop, and the e6 pawn may also serve to be a target at some point. }
