[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...c5 4.Ngf3 without 4...cxd4"]
[Black "3...c5 Introduction "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ This is the critical move nowadays, and has put a lot of people off of the French Tarrasch. I don't think matters are hopeless, but doubtless it is a good move. Black opens the centre at a moment when the Knight has committed to d2, whereas 3.Nc3 c5?! would be quite risky. }
4. Ngf3
{ A small deviation from the first course, although I do intend on recommending similar lines. Essentially, I would like to bypass the line  4.exd5  exd5  5.Ngf3  a6!?  , which stops Bb5  (+)  , thereby avoiding any pins or piece swaps.    Now, on  4.Ngf3  a6  , we can play  5.dxc5  Bxc5  6.Bd3  , transposing to the  3...a6  variation in the sidelines chapter. It's not a huge deal whether you start with  4.exd5  or  4.Ngf3  intending exd5 on the next turn, but this is my preferred move order, just by a bit. }
4... cxd4
{ This is the key move. Now,  5.Nxd4  is possible, but I'm going to suggest... }
5. exd5
{ when  5...Qxd5  will now reach the subject of the next chapter; what is essentially the main line of the French Tarrasch at the moment. }
