[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...c5 4.Ngf3 without 4...cxd4"]
[Black "4...Nc6 with 6...cxd4 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6
{ This is one of Black's major moves in this position, tending to lead to positions where he has an Isolated Queen's Pawn. }
5. exd5 exd5
{ The usual recapture in this position.   The problem with  5...Qxd5  is that we transpose into the position after  3...c5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.Ngf3  Nc6?!  , where Black 'always' takes on  d4  instead. Returning to the present line,  5...Qxd5  6.Bc4  6...Qd6  would allow  7.Ne4  , and after  6...Qd8  , White can either play  7.Nb3  cxd4  8.O-O  with a transposition to the next chapter, or try to exploit Black's move order with  7.dxc5!?  (when I think Black would normally have liked to recapture with the Queen rather than the Bishop)  (. To sum up, there are no benefits to Black choosing this move order to reach ...Qxd5 systems over 4...cxd4; White can transpose to the main line, but has an additional option as well.) }
6. Bb5
{ White develops a piece, pins the Knight on c6, and thus indirectly fights for control over the key d4 square. }
6... cxd4
{ The main move by far is  6...Bd6  , losing a tempo with the Bishop after  7.dxc5  Bxc5  . The question is, can Black do without losing a tempo like this? The text is one such attempt. }
7. Nxd4
{ This is supposed to be harmless   7.Qe2+  is arguably the main try theoretically  , but it looks to me like a simple enough way to play against this variation. White recaptures his pawn, and can follow up by developing normally, and I don't see why he shouldn't have a standard slight plus. }
7... Bd7
{ So, Black has saved time with his King's Bishop, but, unfortunately for him, now is compelled to misplace his Queen's Bishop. }
8. N2f3
{ Clearing the way for the c1 Bishop whilst solidifying control over d4. } 8...
Bd6
{ The problem with Black's development is that due to the upcoming 0-0 and Re1  (+)  , he has to ever so slightly misplace one of his pieces. Either he goes ...Bd6 and ...Nge7 or he goes ...Nf6 and ...Be7. }
9. O-O Nge7
{ As we'll see several times over the course of this chapter,  9...Nf6  10.Re1+  is annoying, leading Black to place his Knight on the less active  e7  square. }
10. Re1 O-O 11. c3
{ There's really no need to go much deeper: it's a standard IQP where Black has a slightly misplaced Bishop on d7. White will probably develop his Bishop to g5, and drop the b5 Bishop back to d3, now that there's no longer any pin along the a4-e8 diagonal. }
