1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bb5 Qe7+
{ This is a pretty strange looking move  (at least to me)  which has become relatively popular lately. }
7. Be2
{ Oddly,  7.Qe2  Qxe2  8.Kxe2  gives Black decent play in the Queenless middlegame due to White's displaced King, despite the fact that exchanges normally favour the side facing the IQP. Anyways, White wastes a tempo with Bb5-e2, but Black will inevitably need to spend a move himself to get his Queen off the e-file. }
7... Qc7
{ Freeing the f8 Bishop, and avoiding trouble on the e-file once Re1 hits the board. Now, it's again just a standard IQP, where the value of Black's ...Qc7 move can be questioned. }
8. O-O Nf6 9. Re1 Be6
{ 9...Be7  isn't a productive way to block the e-file, as after  10.dxc5  , he may remember that he was supposed to be using that Bishop to recapture on  c5  . The text is a bit risky as well, however. }
10. Bd3
{ with the idea of Bf5.   Perhaps Black's best move at this point is  10...0-0-0  , although for obvious reasons he may not be so happy playing that. }
