[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bb5 Bd6
{ So, to sum up, Black's alternatives to this 'tempo-sacrifice' involve making some other concession instead. Therefore, Black normally does accept this, and gets on with his fluid development. }
7. dxc5
{ Of course, now is the right time to capture, only after Black moves his f8 Bishop. }
7... Bxc5 8. O-O Ne7 { 8...Nf6  9.Re1+  would have been awkward to meet. } 9.
Nb3
{ The important thing to remember is not to play  9.Re1?  , as I have in more blitz games than I'm willing to admit. I suppose I take solace in the fact that both Ivanchuk and Yusupov overlooked  9...Bxf2+!  in a Candidates game in 1991. Anyways,  9.Nb3  is an excellent move, gaining time on the  c5  Bishop, freeing the  c1  Bishop, and gaining control over d4. }
9... Bb6
{ Less common than  9...Bd6  . Despite maintaining control over  d4  , it allows White to neutralize the Bishop more easily using his own Dark Squared Bishop. }
10. Re1
{ Intending Be3, to neutralize its counterpart on b6. Now, ...Bxf2+ doesn't work, because with the Knight on b3, White can block with a Knight on d4, covering the Bishop. }
10... O-O 11. Be3
{ Challenging the Bishop's nice diagonal, and once again fighting for d4. }
11... Bf5 12. c3 Be4 13. Bc5
{ An interesting move.  13.Bxb6  Qxb6  would, effectively, be exchanging on Black's terms, as his control over d4 would increase. As well, though, there's the idea of ...Nf5 to worry about, compelling the exchange on b6. Therefore, White steps away from that, pinning the e7 Knight, and prepares to play Nfd4, perhaps f3, and then only exchange on b6 once he feels he's adequately taken control over d4. }
