[White "3...c5 4.Ngf3 without 4...cxd4"]
[Black "4...Nc6 with 6...Bd6 and 9...Bd6 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8.
O-O Ne7 9. Nb3 Bd6
{ The main move. This Bishop faces White's Kingside, and can't be easily neutralized by its counterpart. However, White generally has an easier time in the fight over d4. }
10. Re1 O-O 11. Bd3
{ This is a good move. As Black has now castled, the Bishop has served its function on b5  (pinning the Black Knight)   , and can now repurpose itself. From  d3  , it discourages  11...Bf5  (as that would potentially result in a trade of pieces)  , and prevents  11...Bg4  , due to  12.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  13.Ng5+  Kg8  14.Qxg4  . }
11... h6
{ A multi-purpose move; stopping Bg5 and 'threatening' ...Bg4, as White no longer has Bxh7+ in reply. }
12. h3 { ...and White stops ...Bg4. } 12... Bf5 13. c3
{ This, again, relates to the point of ensuring that exchanges are made on our terms.  13.Bxf5  Nxf5  , while playable, would assist Black in bringing a piece to control  d4  . Meanwhile if the exchange is made on  d3  , the second player would benefit much less. }
13... Qd7 14. Bxf5
{ Okay, so I'm aware what I just said, but in fact, in this case, White can use the weakness of d5 to ensure that Black doesn't get too active. }
14... Nxf5 15. Kf1
{ Now, with ...Bh2+ no longer being check, White threatens to take on d5.   15...Bc7  is bad because of  16.Nc5  .   15...Nce7  is bad because of  16.g4  .   That more or less leaves the retreat  15...Nfe7  , or  15...Be7  which allows White to play  Bf4  at some point. Neither of these are particularly ideal for Black.   By the way,  15.Kh1  is also possible, but my computer insists this the text is stronger. The pawn on  f2  does look a bit weak not being covered by either the King or the Rook, but of course it’s nothing disastrous. }
