1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8.
O-O Ne7 9. Nb3 Bd6
{ The main move. This Bishop faces White's Kingside, and can't be easily neutralized by its counterpart. However, White generally has an easier time in the fight over d4. }
10. Re1 O-O 11. Bd3 h6
{ A multi-purpose move; stopping Bg5 and 'threatening' ...Bg4, as White no longer has Bxh7+ in reply. }
12. h3 { ...and White stops ...Bg4. } 12... Nf5 13. c3
{ Fighting for d4, but also planning the idea Bc2 and Qd3. } 13... Bc7
{ This is an interesting move, planning ...Qd6, a plan similar to one White often executes in this line. White should then watch out for ...Nh4, when he may end up finding himself facing quite an annoying check on h2. }
14. Bc2 Qd6 15. Qd3
{ Of course, ...Nh4 is not available to Black now, as this piece is now pinned. }
15... g6 16. Qd2
{ Thematic - the ...g6 advance left h6 slightly weak, so White goes after it. Note that in the current position, ...Bf8 is not available as a defense for h6, so Black has to make a slightly more awkward move. }
16... h5 17. Qg5
{ Hopping into the newly weakened square. This looks a bit unusual, but ...Nh4 is prevented, and White can continue developing his pieces and fighting for d4. He can also eliminate the Knight on f5 at a moment of his choosing, essentially winning the battle for the d4 square at the cost of the Bishop pair. Black is quite active, so play is still very complex, but White should be a bit better. }
