1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8.
O-O Ne7 9. Nb3 Bd6
{ The main move. This Bishop faces White's Kingside, and can't be easily neutralized by its counterpart. However, White generally has an easier time in the fight over d4. }
10. Re1 O-O 11. Bd3 h6
{ A multi-purpose move; stopping Bg5 and 'threatening' ...Bg4, as White no longer has Bxh7+ in reply. }
12. h3 { ...and White stops ...Bg4. } 12... Nf5 13. c3 Qf6
{ Black is playing actively and well. Should nothing in particular happen over the next few moves, Black will be excellently placed, with his share of the activity and control over d4. Therefore, White has to find a way to disturb Black. }
14. Bc2 Rd8 15. Qd3 g6
{ Stopping g2-g4, which would've won the Knight. Now, White has a wide choice from many decent options. }
16. Bd2
{ White makes a simple developing move and awaits further events.16.a4 is a decent move, gaining some space on the Queenside.  16.Nh2  is quite a tempting move, menacing  Ng4  , which targets both the Queen and the  h6  pawn. This does, however, lead to complications, and I wanted to keep things simple in this line whenever possible.  16.Qd2   unlike in the previous variation, this can be met by  16...Bf8  (is the move I previously recommended based on a wonderful game by Michael Adams, and is probably still good as well. White should be ever so slightly better, although again, it's very complex and playable for both sides.) }
