[White "3...c5 4.Ngf3 without 4...cxd4"]
[Black "4...Nf6 5.exd5 exd5 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nf6
{ This is another extremely important move to consider. Black avoids the Bb5 pin, but White can still give check from b5 in the hopes of swapping off a set of pieces. }
5. exd5 exd5 { This is by far the main move, leading to an IQP position. } 6.
Bb5+ Bd7
{ In this line, Black avoids the pin of his Knight, but does have to trade off a set of minor pieces, and therefore it is arguably a little less ambitious. Piece trades generally help the side facing the IQP @@StartBracket@@which will almost certainly occur, after the d4 and c5 pawns are exchanged for each other@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 8. O-O
{ There are a few differences between this variation and the last. Firstly, there's a set of pieces off the board - a good start for White. However, Black is going to avoid losing time with his Bishop after dxc5 - he's poised to recapture with the Knight, which can subsequently go to the active e4 square, or to e6, from where it influences d4. }
8... Be7 9. dxc5
{ White should be waiting for the Bishop to go to e7 before capturing on c5, to avoid giving Black the opportunity to play ...Bxc5 in one turn. }
9... Nxc5 10. Nd4
{ Perhaps the most accurate move. To quote Nitrils and GM Aagaard in 'Playing the French'; 'It is important to threaten to play ♘f5 , forcing the queen to go to d7. This will help White to activate the d2-knight. 10.Nb3 is met by 10...Nce4 and if now 11. Nfd4 then Black has gained the possibility of defending the f5-square with 11.. .Nd6, as recommended by GM Eingorn. I like the look of the knight on d6, as it covers the important c4- and e4-squares. White may still have an edge, although my analysis has not proved this.' }
10... Qd7 11. N2f3
{ My original suggestion was  11.N2b3  , with the idea to play  11...Nce4  12.f3  Nd6  13.Nc5  Qc8  14.Nd3  , with quite a harmonious arrangement of the Knights. The central squares are nicely covered and, importantly, ...Nc4 does not hit  b2  , because that square is guarded by the  d3  Knight.     Unfortunately, Miedema suggested  11...O-O!  is his book, a new move for me. It's quite surprising, at least personally, that Black would be willing to exchange another set of pieces, but it seems that the activity he gets in return is enough to compensate.   The text instead aims for the d3 square via the route e5 to d3. }
11... O-O 12. Ne5 Qc8
{ 12...Qc7  13.Bf4  should give White some chances for an advantage, with one important point being that the  f5  square remains undefended, and so  Nf5xe7  is very much in the air. }
13. Be3
{ Simply developing.   13.Nd3  is totally possible as well, but there's no need to play it just yet. }
13... Re8 14. h3
{ Guarding against the annoying ...Ng4, thereby freeing the e5 Knight to drop back to d3. }
14... Bf8 15. Nd3
{ Stockfish 12 gives White a modest plus of around +0.3, while Leela Zero is somewhat more fond of Black's position, giving an assessment of around even. Regardless, my sense is that White should be relatively comfortable here, with a set of pieces already swapped off and nice control over d4. }
