1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 cxd4 5. exd5 Qxd5
{ This is the starting point of what is essentially the critical line of the French Tarrasch these days. Black is temporarily up a pawn, but White can regain it with Nb3xd4. First, however, White should develop a piece with a gain of tempo. }
6. Bc4 Qd7
{ This is a weird looking move, but it's become quite trendy lately. Basically the point is to set up with ...Qc7 and ...Bd6, but without leaving the Queen open to Ne4 @@StartBracket@@like ...Qd6 would@@EndBracket@@. Therefore, Black doesn't have to play an early ...Nf6 to prevent this, and might deploy said Knight to e7 instead. Frankly, I don't think it's possible to get much of a tangible edge in this variation, so we may as well go for a tricky variation which puts Black under pressure. }
7. O-O
{ I previously recommended a delayed castling approach with 7.Nb3, but I no longer think this is so great. }
7... Nc6 8. Nb3 Nf6 9. Qe2
{ Essentially, the foundation of our strategy against Queen retreats other than ...Qd6 is to delay collecting the pawn on d4. Since the ...e5 push is not supported by the Queen at the moment, we can take our time, and pick it up in the way we want to; after Qe2 and Rd1. }
9... Be7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. Nbxd4 Nxd4 12. Rxd4
{ White should be a bit better. Black has the typically solid position for this line, but White is more actively placed than he usually is, with Bf4. Ne5 and even Bd3 and Rh4 in the air. }
