7... Nc6 8. Nb3 Nf6 9. Qe2
{ Essentially, the foundation of our strategy against Queen retreats other than ...Qd6 is to delay collecting the pawn on d4. Since the ...e5 push is not supported by the Queen at the moment, we can take our time, and pick it up in the way we want to; after Qe2 and Rd1. }
9... a6 10. a4 { Allowing ...b5 is probably not ideal. } 10... Bd6 11. Rd1 e5
{ This is the critical line. Of course, d4 isn't genuinely defended because of the pin, but nonetheless, it does lead to forcing play. }
12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 Qe7 14. Rxd6
{ 14.Rh4 is the alternative but this exchange sac looks to me like the hardest to face. Don't be put off by White's poor score in the database, it's just important to remember the next few moves. }
14... Qxd6 15. b3
{ Well, this is the point. The idea of Ba3 keeps Black's King in the centre. }
15... e4 { This is probably the best. } 16. Ba3 Qf4 17. Qe1
{ A subtle but important move. The idea is Qa5, when suddenly Qc5 with a mate threat on g7 becomes very potent. In fact, Black only has one move that doesn't lose immediately here. }
17... Be6 18. Qa5
{ Another very important move; stopping long castling and setting up Qc5 once again. White's score in practice was poor after the exchange sacrifice, but in limited practice he's done pretty well from this position. }
18... Rc8
{ This is natural, stopping Qc5, but it turns out to be just about losing. Here's one sample variation: }
19. Ne5
{ This brings a new piece into the attack, but also cuts off Black's Queen from the defense, at least temporarily, meaning Qb4 and a subsequent Qd6 @@StartBracket@@after ...Rc7@@EndBracket@@ is on the table as a very dangerous idea. }
19... Ng4
{ Attempting to trade off a set of pieces as well as allow the Queen to participate in the defense. }
20. Bb5+
{ This isn't the only good move, but it is particularly strong. Black just doesn't have a defense against the upcoming attack. }
20... axb5 21. Qxb5+ Rc6 { or  21...Kd8  22.Rd1+  , and so forth. } 22. Nxc6
Qxh2+ 23. Kf1 Qh1+ 24. Ke2 Qxa1
{ Not best, but now we get to see White's point. } 25. Ne5+ Kd8 26. Qa5+ Kc8
{ 26...Ke8  27.Qa8+  leads to mate. } 27. Bd6 { Chess is fun sometimes. } *

