[White "3...c5 4.Ngf3 cxd4 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Bc4 Qd6 "]
[Black "10...Bd7 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 cxd4 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. Bc4 Qd6 7. O-O
{ Don't play  7.Nb3  Qb4+  . } 7... Nf6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7
{ With this move, Black is simply developing and dissuading Nb5, while hinting at maybe castling long. }
11. b3
{ My original intention was to recommend  11.c3  , with the idea of Qe2 or Qf3. I recommended this in my earlier repertoire, as did John Shaw in his French Tarrasch book.   However, I stumbled upon the reply  11...Qc7  12.Qe2  a6!  13.g3  e5!  , which put me off, as I couldn't find any advantage at all. Funnily enough, there are only three games with this idea in my database, all three of them correspondence games by the same player; Dennis Doren. So shoutout to that guy. }
11... a6
{ Stopping any ideas on Nb5 White may be considering; which is quite annoying, especially when Black is planning ...Qc7 and ...Bd6. }
12. Bb2 Qc7 13. Qe2 O-O-O
{ Black has executed his plan, and White has developed his minor pieces, so it's time to come up with an idea. When Black castles long in this line, there's one particular piece re-deployment that is often strong, and it's worth adding to your toolbox of ideas. }
14. Nf3 Bd6 15. Ne5
{ Targetting f7, hitting the Bishop on d7, perhaps taking away the otherwise desirable c6 square from it, and so forth. }
