1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 cxd4 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. Bc4 Qd6 7. O-O
{ Don't play  7.Nb3  Qb4+  . } 7... Nf6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7
{ With this move, Black is simply developing and dissuading Nb5, while hinting at maybe castling long. }
11. b3 O-O-O
{ This time Black omits ...a7-a6. We'll try to make him pay for that. } 12. a4
h5
{ Black is planning his own attack, involving ...Ng4. If White goes h2-h3, Black is probably going to plop his Knight there anyway. }
13. Nb5 Qb8
{ It seems like White should have a massive initiative in the endgame after  13...Qxd1  14.Rxd1  , with Nxa7 threatened, and ideas like Nd6+ and Bf4 all over the place. }
14. Qe2 a6
{ In one game, White contented himself with going back with  15.Nd4  . I gotta say, that's probably what I would do too. The computer showed me something better though... }
15. Be3 { Yep. Ever seen a fishing pole on the Queenside? } 15... axb5
{ Well, otherwise Black faces destruction on the dark squares. Now, the a-file opens, however, and White gets a very strong attack. }
16. axb5 Ng4 17. g3
{ Stopping the threat on h2, and also maybe introducing Bf4 into the picture. My computer trusts that White has great compensation, and I believe it. If you need further convincing, you can try a 'fun' exercise and play this position out against a computer, and see how that goes. }
