[White "3...c5 4.Ngf3 cxd4 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Bc4 Qd6 "]
[Black "10...Be7 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 cxd4 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. Bc4 Qd6 7. O-O
{ Don't play  7.Nb3  Qb4+  . } 7... Nf6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Be7
{ This is Anish Giri's recommendation in Lifetime Repertoires: the French. I used to think it was a solid but passive move, where White could count on a small advantage. Unfortunately, after checking Giri's course, I found out that he gave an important refinement that I wasn't previously aware of, which appears to - objectively - equalize. Sad but true. Well, it's still a chess game, and I prefer White in a practical game in the resulting positions. }
11. c3
{ Covering the Knight, and thus intending Qf3.   11.b3  O-O  12.Bb2  Qf4!  seems to disrupt the set-up White is going for, and thus should be fine for Black. }
11... O-O 12. Qf3 Qc7
{ The reason why 10...Be7 has the reputation of being solid but passive is that if you delay ...Be7 with Black, you may end up with an opportunity to deploy it more active on d6 after this Queen move. Delaying Kingside development does of course come with its own risks, however. }
13. Bb3 Bd7
{ This is the 'old main line', I suppose. The following sequence should give White a tiny edge: }
14. Bf4 e5
{ 14...Bd6  15.Bxd6  Qxd6  16.Qxb7  . But keep this in mind for later. } 15.
Bg3 Bd6 { Now, White can very briefly pick up the Bishop pair with... } 16. Nf5
Bxf5 17. Qxf5 e4
{ Okay, Black can swap off one of White's Bishops, but it's still a Bishop against a Knight in a pretty open position. }
18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Rad1
{ White should have slightly better chances here. Again, it's a Bishop against a Knight, and the advanced e-pawn could prove to be a weakness someday. }
