[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...c5 4.Ngf3 cxd4 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Bc4 Qd6 "]
[Black "10...Be7 2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 cxd4 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. Bc4 Qd6 7. O-O
{ Don't play  7.Nb3  Qb4+  . } 7... Nf6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Be7
{ This is Anish Giri's recommendation in Lifetime Repertoires: the French. I used to think it was a solid but passive move, where White could count on a small advantage. Unfortunately, after checking Giri's course, I found out that he gave an important refinement that I wasn't previously aware of, which appears to - objectively - equalize. Sad but true. Well, it's still a chess game, and I prefer White in a practical game in the resulting positions. }
11. c3
{ Covering the Knight, and thus intending Qf3.    11.b3  O-O  12.Bb2  Qf4!  seems to disrupt the set-up White is going for, and thus should be fine for Black. }
11... O-O 12. Qf3 Qc7
{ The reason why 10...Be7 has the reputation of being solid but passive is that if you delay ...Be7 with Black, you may end up with an opportunity to deploy it more active on d6 after this Queen move. Delaying Kingside development does of course come with its own risks, however. }
13. Bb3 a5
{ I wasn't aware of this move before looking at Giri's course. It seems strong. }
14. a4 Bd7
{ So why does the insertion of ...a5 and a4 help Black.   Well, if we play as we did in the previous variation, with  15.Bf4  , Black can reply not with  15...e5  , but with  15...Bd6!  , and on  16.Bxd6  Qxd6  17.Qxb7  Rab8  , the Bishop on  b3  is no longer defended by the a-pawn, meaning  ...e5  next leaves it in some trouble. }
15. Re1 Qb6 16. Bc2
{ Okay, so this position is equal objectively. That being said, I'd slightly rather play White. One very tempting idea  (and part of the point of White's last)  is Qh3, pointing at h7, which, in tandem with Bg5 can whip up a sudden Kingside attack. The Queen can also swing to g3, which may be effective under the right set of circumstances. Otherwise, the plan may well just be Rb1 to cover b2, followed by developing the Bishop to e3, f4 or g5. It's not much, but in practice I think it's a little bit. It's hard for Black to get fully active, as ...e5 may see that pawn becoming weak, and on ...Bc6, White may consider taking it if his Knight is still on d4  (although sometimes this isn't as effective as it may seem, due to ...bxc6 followed by planting a Knight on d5, as the second player does in one of Giri's variations)  . }
