[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...c5 4.Ngf3 cxd4 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Bc4 Qd6 "]
[Black "10...a6 Introduction "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 cxd4 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. Bc4 Qd6 7. O-O Nf6 8.
Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 a6
{ Covering the b5 square, and preparing a later ...b5, in Najdorf style @@StartBracket@@this is sort of a Sicilian-esque structure, after all@@EndBracket@@. I'm going to be real with you. I ran my computer all night on this position, and when I woke up, I was pretty unsurprised to be greeted with 0.00 after all of White's major moves. On the other hand, there's reason to be optimistic. Black's life is hardly easy in this variation, because White has a number of tricky tries, and Black has to be prepared for all of them. White's position definitely still contains venom. }
11. Re1
{ Good move - with Black not currently poised to castle in either direction, it's important to introduce the idea of Nf5 @@StartBracket@@hitting g7 if the Bishop leaves f8@@EndBracket@@ . }
11... Qc7
{ Attacking the  c4  Bishop and clearing the way for  ...Bd6  . Now, I'm going to show you  12.Bd3  ; a tricky alternative, but mostly harmless if Black is accurate and  12.Bf1  ; a currently trendy move, and Shaw's recommendation, which I think might be White's best shot  .   12.Qe2  was my previous suggestion, but after the brilliantly prophylactic  12...h6!!  , White seems to have nothing. }
12. Bf1
{ White tucks the Bishop away on f1. It can potentially re-emerge on g2 after g2-g3. This move was Shaw's recommendation, and I really don't want to just repeat all of his lines. That being said, it might genuinely just be the most promising move at White's disposal. Incidentally, it was not mentioned in Ntirlis and Aagard's Playing the French, as I assume it was not yet very well known at that time. }
