{ Covering f6, but the Bishop is also somewhat exposed here; i.e. to Nf3 ideas. }
16. c3 Bd7 { A simple developing move. } 17. Qe2
{ Preparing to bring a Rook to d1 while hitting the Bishop on e5. He doesn't terribly want to retreat and allow a capture on f6, so his hand is basically forced. }
17... Bxd4 18. cxd4 Nd5 19. Rac1
{ When we can make Black take on d4 in this line, it kind of feels like we've achieved something. Now, we've got two Bishops and potential attacking chances on the Kingside. Granted, we are now in possession of an isolated pawn, well blockaded by the Knight on d5. Also, whenever we attack h7 with something like Qe4 or Qh5, Black can always reply ...f5, when we lack a Knight to land on the e5 outpost. I think Black should be fine here, but I also think this is definitely worth trying it you aren't convinced by the 12. Bf1 line, or you think your opponent might be prepared for that. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...c5 4.Ngf3 cxd4 5.exd5 Qxd5 6.Bc4 Qd6 "]
[Black "12.Bf1 Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 cxd4 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. Bc4 Qd6 7. O-O Nf6 8.
Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 a6
{ Covering the b5 square, and preparing a later ...b5, in Najdorf style  (this is sort of a Sicilian-esque structure, after all)  . I'm going to be real with you. I ran my computer all night on this position, and when I woke up, I was pretty unsurprised to be greeted with 0.00 after all of White's major moves. On the other hand, there's reason to be optimistic. Black's life is hardly easy in this variation, because White has a number of tricky tries, and Black has to be prepared for all of them. White's position definitely still contains venom. }
11. Re1
{ Good move - with Black not currently poised to castle in either direction, it's important to introduce the idea of Nf5  (hitting g7 if the Bishop leaves f8)  . }
11... Qc7 { Attacking the c4 Bishop and clearing the way for ...Bd6. } 12. Bf1
{ White tucks the Bishop away on f1. It can potentially re-emerge on g2 after g2-g3. This move was Shaw's recommendation, and I really don't want to just repeat all of his lines. That being said, it might genuinely just be the most promising move at White's disposal. Incidentally, it was not mentioned in Ntirlis and Aagard's Playing the French, as I assume it was not yet very well known at that time. }
12... Be7
{ This is fairly popular. Black simply blocks the e-file and gets ready to castle, thereby not having to worry about any Nf5 ideas. Objectively, Black should be fine, but White has ever-so-slightly the more pleasant position. }
13. Qf3 O-O 14. Bf4 Bd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Rad1
{ Again, I'm not going to overstate White's chances, because he only scores 50% from this position. That being said, he's gotten all of his pieces developed, while Black's Queenside is still at home, and beginning to set the Queenside pawns in motion with c2-c4 is a major idea at his disposal. Black, for his part, is currently a bit too passive to start expanding his own majority with ...e6-e5, as that pawn may become a target, and Nf5 also seems quite annoying in reply. }
16... Qc7 17. c4
{ This is an important part of White's position. With Black not very actively placed at the moment, White should take this opportunity to begin the process of setting his Queenside pawns in motion. }
