[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ This is a flexible move popularized by Alexander Morozevich. Black develops a piece, while, in effect, waiting for White to do something, so he can react accordingly. There are some sharp lines beginning with either  4.Ngf3  or  4.Bd3  . However, a venomous positional treatment has come to the fore, and this is what I'll suggest. }
4. e5 c5 5. c3
{ The old move was  5.Qg4!?  , but it turns out that the time Black will gain chasing the Queen is worth the minor inconvenience from playing  5...Kf8! }
5... Nc6
{ I suppose Black can also start with  5...cxd4  , but he tends not to commit to that exchange so early.  In any event after a seemingly inevitable ...Nc6, it'll simply transpose. }
6. Bd3
{ I think this is the only way for White to get his ideal♗d3/♘e2/♘f3 set-up in. It's important that this move, in fact, does not hang a pawn... }
6... cxd4
{ Black probably shouldn't put off this exchange for too long, as eventually d4xc5 may become very strong. }
7. cxd4 Nxd4 8. Qg4 { ...and Black loses. d4 and g7 are forked. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...Be7"]
[Black "4...c5 with 6...cxd4 7.cxd4 Nh6 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ This is a flexible move popularized by Alexander Morozevich. Black develops a piece, while, in effect, waiting for White to do something, so he can react accordingly. There are some sharp lines beginning with either  4.Ngf3  or  4.Bd3  . However, a venomous positional treatment has come to the fore, and this is what I'll suggest. }
4. e5 c5 5. c3
{ The old move was  5.Qg4!?  , but it turns out that the time Black will gain chasing the Queen is worth the minor inconvenience from playing  5...Kf8! }
5... Nc6
{ I suppose Black can also start with  5...cxd4  , but he tends not to commit to that exchange so early. In any event after a seemingly inevitable  ...Nc6  , it'll simply transpose. }
6. Bd3
{ I think this is the only way for White to get his ideal♗d3/♘e2/♘f3 set-up in. It's important that this move, in fact, does not hang a pawn... }
6... cxd4
{ Black probably shouldn't put off this exchange for too long, as eventually d4xc5 may become very strong. }
7. cxd4 Nh6 { Heading for f5 to pressure the centre. } 8. Ne2
{ I previously gave  8.Ndf3  , which is still totally fine. Somehow it just feels simpler to start with  Ne2  , preparing castling, whenever this option is available to us. }
8... f6
{ Black breaks in the centre. It's now possible to react in a variety of ways.  9.f4  is maybe not so good now that Black's  g8  Knight is already developed and ready to pressure the centre, although we'll see this idea later. Covering the pawn on  e5  with  9.Nf3  and opening the centre with  9.exf6  are both options. }
9. exf6 Bxf6 10. Nf3
{ This is a standard French Tarrasch type position, albeit not a type which we've discussed that much in this course so far. Essentially, White gets to play against the weakened e5 square and backwards e6 pawn, but Black has some activity to compensate. This sort of position would normally be reached with Black's Bishop on d6 and Knight on f6, so this version is a little unusual. White can castle and play moves like Bf4 and Rc1. Black can go ...Nf5 and ...Qb6 to put pressure on White's centre, although this can be met by retreating the d3 Bishop to cover d4 with the Queen, as well as a timely Bxf5. The aforementioned capture is something we'll see again - it allows Black to play ...e6xf5 and rid himself of a potential weakness, but also limits some of Black's activity, while the weak Dark Squares and bad French Bishop remain. }
