[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ This is a flexible move popularized by Alexander Morozevich. Black develops a piece, while, in effect, waiting for White to do something, so he can react accordingly. There are some sharp lines beginning with either  4.Ngf3  or  4.Bd3  . However, a venomous positional treatment has come to the fore, and this is what I'll suggest. }
4. e5 c5 5. c3
{ The old move was  5.Qg4!?  , but it turns out that the time Black will gain chasing the Queen is worth the minor inconvenience from playing  5...Kf8! }
5... Nc6
{ I suppose Black can also start with  5...cxd4  , but he tends not to commit to that exchange so early. In any event after a seemingly inevitable  ...Nc6  , it'll simply transpose. }
6. Bd3
{ I think this is the only way for White to get his ideal♗d3/♘e2/♘f3 set-up in. It's important that this move, in fact, does not hang a pawn... }
6... cxd4
{ Black probably shouldn't put off this exchange for too long, as eventually d4xc5 may become very strong. }
7. cxd4 Nh6 { Heading for f5 to pressure the centre. } 8. Ne2
{ I previously gave  8.Ndf3  , which is still totally fine. Somehow it just feels simpler to start with  Ne2  , preparing castling, whenever this option is available to us. }
8... Nf5 9. Nf3
{ White covers his centre very solidly with his two Knights. If White can consolidate his space advantage, he's often just simply better. }
9... Qb6
{ This is Black's most ambitious move, attacking the d4 pawn for a third time. White does have a good reply, however. }
10. O-O
{ Note that the threat to d4 is currently illusory due to Bb5+ at the end of the line. }
10... Bd7
{ Black's moves can be played in a number of move orders; whether he begins with...Bd7, ...Qb6 or...Nh6-f5 isn't terribly significant. However, it is important to notice that, with the a4-e8 diagonal blocked, White really does have to do something about the d4 pawn. }
11. Bxf5
{ Perhaps slightly surprising, but strong. Giving up the good Bishop like this is not normally advisable, however, it is justified here by several factors:   1. Black's pawns are weakened.   2. It releases pressure ond4  , thus enabling White's Knights to do other things.   3. On a related note,f4  will be a nice square for the  e2  Knight.   4. And very importantly, White is immediately able to rid Black of his Bishop pair by following up with♗g5  .  
Incidentally,  11.Kh1  is also a decent move. }
11... exf5 12. Bg5 Bxg5 13. Nxg5 h6 14. Nh3 { To f4. } 14... g5
{ Grabbing on b2 seems a bit much, with ♘hf4, ♕d3, either Rook to b1 followed by taking on b7 in the air. }
15. f4 g4 16. Nf2
{ Black's Kingside pawns might look menacing, but there is no attack forthcoming. Meanwhile, White's Knights will dominate the closed position, and Black's King will struggle for total safety. }
