[White "3...Be7"]
[Black "4...c5 with 6...cxd4 7.cxd4 Qb6 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ This is a flexible move popularized by Alexander Morozevich. Black develops a piece, while, in effect, waiting for White to do something, so he can react accordingly. There are some sharp lines beginning with either  4.Ngf3  or  4.Bd3  . However, a venomous positional treatment has come to the fore, and this is what I'll suggest. }
4. e5 c5 5. c3
{ The old move was  5.Qg4!?  , but it turns out that the time Black will gain chasing the Queen is worth the minor inconvenience from playing  5...Kf8! }
5... Nc6
{ I suppose Black can also start with  5...cxd4  , but he tends not to commit to that exchange so early. In any event after a seemingly inevitable  ...Nc6  , it'll simply transpose. }
6. Bd3
{ I think this is the only way for White to get his ideal♗d3/♘e2/♘f3 set-up in. It's important that this move, in fact, does not hang a pawn... }
6... cxd4
{ Black probably shouldn't put off this exchange for too long, as eventually d4xc5 may become very strong. }
7. cxd4 Qb6
{ So, we've established that Black can't take on d4 just yet, so he puts further pressure on it in standard French style. }
8. Ndf3
{ White has to be a little careful; we want to setup with Ng1-e2 and Nd2-f3, but it's crucial to start with the latter, so that Bb5+ discovery is available should Black try to take on d4. }
8... Nh6 9. Ne2 Nf5 10. O-O
{ This transposes to the position we looked at via the move order 7...Nh6 8.Ne2 Nf5 9.Ndf3 Qb6 10.0-0. Move orders are largely variable in this line. }
*

