[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...Be7"]
[Black "4...c5 with 6...cxd4 7.cxd4 Qb6 3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ This is a flexible move popularized by Alexander Morozevich. Black develops a piece, while, in effect, waiting for White to do something, so he can react accordingly. There are some sharp lines beginning with either  4.Ngf3  or  4.Bd3  . However, a venomous positional treatment has come to the fore, and this is what I'll suggest. }
4. e5 c5 5. c3
{ The old move was  5.Qg4!?  , but it turns out that the time Black will gain chasing the Queen is worth the minor inconvenience from playing  5...Kf8! }
5... Nc6
{ I suppose Black can also start with  5...cxd4  , but he tends not to commit to that exchange so early. In any event after a seemingly inevitable  ...Nc6  , it'll simply transpose. }
6. Bd3
{ I think this is the only way for White to get his ideal♗d3/♘e2/♘f3 set-up in. It's important that this move, in fact, does not hang a pawn... }
6... cxd4
{ Black probably shouldn't put off this exchange for too long, as eventually d4xc5 may become very strong. }
7. cxd4 Qb6
{ So, we've established that Black can't take on d4 just yet, so he puts further pressure on it in standard French style. }
8. Ndf3
{ White has to be a little careful; we want to setup with Ng1-e2 and Nd2-f3, but it's crucial to start with the latter, so that Bb5+ discovery is available should Black try to take on d4. }
8... Bd7
{ Now, the d-pawn's threatened for real. Fortunately, we're just in time to securely defend it. }
9. Ne2 Nb4 { A very aggressive plan. } 10. Bb1
{ Of course White needs to retain his good Bishop. } 10... Bb5
{ A threatening follow-up - this combined with ...Qa6 will cause White some temporary difficulties, but he can defend himself, leaving Black's set-up looking a bit strange. }
11. O-O Qa6 12. Re1
{ Black's managed to create a battery, and now has the opportunity to stick a piece on d3. }
12... Bd3
{ This essentially just ends up amounting to an incredibly long-winded exchange of Bishops. }
13. Bd2 Bxb1 14. Rxb1 Qxa2
{ Black can't really afford to grab this pawn. Instead he should make some normal move, but White's centre is very strong, and the trade of Light Squared Bishops pretty much ensures that e6 will be weak if Black ever tries ...f6. He also has yet to complete his Kingside development, which is still somewhat awkward. }
15. Bxb4 Bxb4 16. Ra1 Qc4 { 16...Qxb2  17.Qa4+  and  Reb1  wins for White. }
17. Qa4+ b5 18. Qa6
{ White has infiltrated, and after Rc1, Black is in huge trouble, with a big check on c6 looming. The hanging Rook on e1 actually turns out to be largely irrelevant. }
