[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ This is a flexible move popularized by Alexander Morozevich. Black develops a piece, while, in effect, waiting for White to do something, so he can react accordingly. There are some sharp lines beginning with either  4.Ngf3  or  4.Bd3  . However, a venomous positional treatment has come to the fore, and this is what I'll suggest. }
4. e5 c5 5. c3
{ The old move was  5.Qg4!?  , but it turns out that the time Black will gain chasing the Queen is worth the minor inconvenience from playing  5...Kf8! }
5... Nc6
{ I suppose Black can also start with  5...cxd4  , but he tends not to commit to that exchange so early. In any event after a seemingly inevitable  ...Nc6  , it'll simply transpose. }
6. Bd3
{ I think this is the only way for White to get his ideal♗d3/♘e2/♘f3 set-up in. It's important that this move, in fact, does not hang a pawn... }
6... Nh6
{ Here we'll see an example of what happens if Black tries the ...Nh6-f5/...Qb6 plan without first taking on d4. Essentially, if he waits too long to capture, dxc5 becomes a very attractive possibility for White. }
7. Ndf3 Nf5 8. Ne2 Qb6
{ There's nothing especially wrong with...Qb6 as a concept, but Black should really start with 8...cxd4. Here's why: }
9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. O-O
{ White benefits greatly from not having a fixed target on d4 - he's much more free for active undertakings. A demonstration: }
10... a5
{ Stopping b2-b4, which, in combination with g2-g4, would cause Black some serious problems. }
11. Nf4
{ Threatening Bxf5 followed by Nxd5. Note that if White still had a pawn on d4, the e2 Knight would still likely be stuck defending it. }
11... g6 12. Bxf5 gxf5 13. Nh5
{ and into f6. Black played rather co-operatively throughout this sequence, but it's just meant as an illustration of the dangers of Black's position following dxc5. }
