{ 7...cxd4  8.cxd4  would transpose to 6...cxd4 7.cxd4 Qb6.   Meanwhile,  7...f6  can be met with  8.Ne2  ,  in similar vein to the text, allowing Black to capture on e5 rather than taking on f6. }
8. Ne2 { ...cxd4 was threatened, so White must defend the d4 pawn again. } 8...
f6
{ Once again, 8... cxd4 would transpose to lines covered under the 6...cxd4 heading. The text attempts to free Black's position, but in this case, White is not obliged to play along by capturing on f6. }
9. O-O fxe5 10. dxe5 O-O-O 11. b4
{ White is ripping open the Queenside, with a strong attack. ...c5-c4 would keep the Queenside temporarily closed, but concede the wonderful d4 square for a White Knight. Black's counterplay in these positions tends to be at least partially based on ...g5, but he's a bit behind in this particular case. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3...Be7"]
[Black "4...c5 with 6...Bd7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ This is a flexible move popularized by Alexander Morozevich. Black develops a piece, while, in effect, waiting for White to do something, so he can react accordingly. There are some sharp lines beginning with either  4.Ngf3  or  4.Bd3  . However, a venomous positional treatment has come to the fore, and this is what I'll suggest. }
4. e5 c5 5. c3
{ The old move was  5.Qg4!?  , but it turns out that the time Black will gain chasing the Queen is worth the minor inconvenience from playing  5...Kf8! }
5... Nc6
{ I suppose Black can also start with  5...cxd4  , but he tends not to commit to that exchange so early. In any event after a seemingly inevitable  ...Nc6  , it'll simply transpose. }
6. Bd3
{ I think this is the only way for White to get his ideal♗d3/♘e2/♘f3 set-up in. It's important that this move, in fact, does not hang a pawn... }
6... Bd7 7. Ne2
{ Once again, our Knights belong on e2 and f3, where they both have a function, defend d4 in tandem, and have opportunities on squares such as f4, g5, and potentially d4 and e5. }
7... f6 8. f4
{ This is an interesting option afforded to us by the fact that we started with 7.Ne2 and not 7.Ndf3. Now, play resembles the 3...Nf6 variation, where we have the large c3/d4/e5/f4 centre, and Black currently is not that quick to challenge it. }
