[Black "4...Nh6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Be7
{ This is a flexible move popularized by Alexander Morozevich. Black develops a piece, while, in effect, waiting for White to do something, so he can react accordingly. There are some sharp lines beginning with either  4.Ngf3  or  4.Bd3  . However, a venomous positional treatment has come to the fore, and this is what I'll suggest. }
4. e5 Nh6
{ This is a move Black sometimes plays to avoid the sharp  4...c5  5.Qg4  line. However, given that we weren't intending to go for that variation anyway, and that Black is unlikely to do without  ...c7-c5  for very long, it shouldn't have too much independent significance for us. }
5. Bd3 c5 6. c3
{ ...with play very similar to the rest of the chapter, and seemingly quite likely to transpose. }
