[Black "3...f5 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 f5
{ More of a weakening of the e5 square and the a2-g8 diagonal than anything else. }
4. exf5 exf5 5. Bd3 Nf6 6. Ne2 Bd6 7. Nf3
{ White is just setting up in standard French Tarrasch style. Another typical idea, Bf4, may come to the fore as well, as trading off Dark Squared Bishops will further White's idea of planting a Knight on e5. }
7... O-O 8. O-O c6 9. Bf4
{ After the exchange of Dark Squared Bishops, White will comfortably land his Knight on  e5  , then perhaps play c2-c4 to put pressure on the centre. He is already significantly better. This is the sequence I gave in the original course.  9.c4!?  also seems like a good move, as suggested by the computer, but the text is certainly the most thematic, and therefore the one I will give. }
