[Black "3...f5 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 f5
{ More of a weakening of the e5 square and the a2-g8 diagonal than anything else. }
4. exf5 exf5 5. Bd3 Nf6 6. Ne2 Bd6 7. Nf3
{ White is just setting up in standard French Tarrasch style. Another typical idea, Bf4, may come to the fore as well, as trading off Dark Squared Bishops will further White's idea of planting a Knight on e5. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Nc6 { An attempt to do something active. } 9. c4
{ A standard operation, that seems particularly strong when ...c7-c6 isn't available as a fortifying move. Now, taking on c4 is very risky because White takes back with check, and then plays Ng5, followed maybe by Nf4, when the diagonal is particularly weak. }
9... Nb4 10. c5 Nxd3 11. Qxd3 Be7 12. Bf4
{ White has fantastic control over the Dark Squares, and a potential bind on the Queenside. Black has control over e4, but a Knight that ends up there can eventually be kicked away with f2-f3. }
