1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 g6
{ This is a rare move, which I didn't cover in the original version. g7 is hardly a natural square for the Bishop in the French, so I'll just give one very brief line. }
4. Ngf3 Bg7 5. c3
{ Covering the d4 pawn and thereby somewhat blunting the Bishop's diagonal makes a lot of sense. White can proceed to develop naturally, and before breaking with ...c5, Black has to seriously think about whether his c5 pawn is just hanging. Just on general grounds, it doesn't make that much sense to play 1...e6, and then switch gears and develop the Bishop to g7! }
