1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 b6
{ Another rare move, which we can cover fairly briefly. } 4. Ngf3 Bb7
{ The most obvious move, although the most popular by far has actually been  4...Nf6  . }
5. e5
{ This is different from what I recommended last time, but I think this approach makes sense. The point is that with the Bishop committed to b7, ...Ba6 would cost him a tempo, meaning this may well be a good time to close the centre. }
5... c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Bd3
{ White has a nice position, again because ...b6 in the French is generally played with the intention of ...Ba6 and not ...Bb7. }
