[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3rd Move Sidelines "]
[Black "3...b6 2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 b6
{ Another rare move, which we can cover fairly briefly. } 4. Ngf3 Nf6
{ Now, my initial recommendation,  5.Ne5  , aiming for an improved Exchange Variation, doesn't have that much sting  , because, in the line I gave, when White plays exd5, Black may react with ...Qxd5!, rather than ...exd5, and then play ...c5, with near equality, if not full equality. With the text Black is trying to lure White into some version of the 3...Nf6 line, with White having committed his King's Knight to f3 already. }
5. exd5
{ I think White can just go for this form of Exchange Variation straight up, without doing this Ne5 and Bb5+ stuff. The point is that the Bishop on b7 is not well placed in this fixed structure, blocked by its own pawn on d5. This is rarely really the end of the world, but still, it's a small but pleasant advantage for White. }
5... Qxd5
{ This recapture keeps the diagonal open, but White can gain some time. } 6.
Bc4
{ In typical French Tarrasch style! That's one of the hidden points of Nd2, supporting Bc4 hitting a Queen on d5, which also comes into play in the 3...c5 variation. }
6... Qd8 7. O-O Bb7 8. Qe2
{ White has a nice and pleasant advantage - greater space and greater activity. I suppose the main question is what to do with the d2 Knight. Ne5 and Ndf3 looks like a reasonable plan, followed by Rd1 and developing the Bishop somewhere.   Note that, e.g.  8...Be7  9.Ne5  Qxd4?  runs into  10.Nxf7!  . }
