[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3rd Move Sidelines "]
[Black "3...Ne7 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Ne7
{ This is a strange move. It's a waiting move in some sense, while it also develops a piece. The problem is, the Knight isn't especially well placed here, nor will it be on g6. }
4. Ngf3 Ng6
{ This is one possible interpretation of 3...Ne7. In general, this looks like a really weird square. At some point, White can play g2-g3, pretty much depriving the Knight of a majority of its purpose on this square. In addition h2-h4 tends to more or less force ...h7-h5 in reply, which might make Kingside castling somewhat difficult to play safely. }
5. h4
{ An annoying move to throw in. This virtually forces the reply...h5. As Yevseev points out, Black will subsequently have some difficulties developing and castling because of this errant h-pawn. }
5... h5 6. g3
{ Taking away the f4 square from the Knight. Yevseev says that the main point in favour on the...Ne7-g6 maneuver is to dissuade a move such as Bd3 or Be2 due to...Nf4. However, once White plays g2-g3, the Knight essentially lacks any purpose on g6. The g2 square, of course, may also be used for the Bishop. }
6... c5 7. Bg2
{ I originally gave  7.exd5  here, but it turns out that that line is actually rather dangerous for White if he follows the specific variation I gave.  7.c3!?  has not been tried, but it is also interesting. }
7... cxd4 8. exd5
{ 8.Nxd4  e5  9.Nf5  is also possible, as given by Tzermiadianos. } 8... Qxd5
9. O-O
{ White will probably win the d4 pawn back, owing to his lead in development  (the standard Nb3 is an idea)  , and has a good position. }
*

