1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Ne7
{ This is a strange move. It's a waiting move in some sense, while it also develops a piece. The problem is, the Knight isn't especially well placed here, nor will it be on g6. This is a strange move. It's a waiting move in some sense, while it also develops a piece. The problem is, the Knight isn't especially well placed here, nor will it be on g6. }
4. Ngf3 Ng6
{ This is one possible interpretation of 3...Ne7. In general, this looks like a really weird square. At some point, White can play g2-g3, pretty much depriving the Knight of a majority of its purpose on this square. In addition h2-h4 tends to more or less force ...h7-h5 in reply, which might make Kingside castling somewhat difficult to play safely. }
5. h4
{ An annoying move to throw in. This virtually forces the reply...h5. As Yevseev points out, Black will subsequently have some difficulties developing and castling because of this errant h-pawn. }
5... h5 6. g3
{ Taking away the f4 square from the Knight. Yevseev says that the main point in favour on the...Ne7-g6 maneuver is to dissuade a move such as Bd3 or Be2 due to...Nf4. However, once White plays g2-g3, the Knight essentially lacks any purpose on g6. The g2 square, of course, may also be used for the Bishop. }
6... c5 7. Bg2
{ I originally gave  7.exd5  here, but it turns out that that line is actually rather dangerous for White if he follows the specific variation I gave.  7.c3!?  has not been tried, but it is also interesting. }
7... cxd4 8. exd5
{ 8.Nxd4  e5  9.Nf5  is also possible, as given by Tzermiadianos. } 8... exd5
{ My computer suggests this as the best move. It will lead to a very strange type of IQP position; QGD Tarrasch reminiscent, almost, but with h4 and ...h5 thrown in, and a strange Knight on g6. It's hard to evaluate exactly who this favours; the Knight on g6 is potentially bad, both sides' Kingsides are weak, and ...Bg4 is a more annoying pin because it's more difficult to challenge that piece. In any event, I would certainly take White, but it's complicated. }
9. O-O { 9.Nxd4  Bg4  seems kind of annoying } 9... Nc6 10. Nb3
{ Once again this standard maneuver to pick up the d4 pawn. } 10... Bg4 11.
Nbxd4 Be7 12. Qd3
{ Unpinning. White is better here. It'll always be somewhat awkward for Black to castle Kingside, as unlike us, he doesn't have a nice Bishop tucked away to protect it. The Bishop on g4 looks nice, but at some point, we can start considering Nh2 to harass it. In the meantime, we have nice play against the IQP, which we've blockaded, and also have the g5 square for our use. }
