[Black "3...Ne7 3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Ne7
{ This is a strange move. It's a waiting move in some sense, while it also develops a piece. The problem is, the Knight isn't especially well placed here, nor will it be on g6. This is a strange move. It's a waiting move in some sense, while it also develops a piece. The problem is, the Knight isn't especially well placed here, nor will it be on g6. }
4. Ngf3 Nd7 5. Bd3
{ Given Black's slightly passive looking development, the alternative  5.c4!?  very much tempted me, but after  5...g6!  , it looks like the  d4  pawn might come under pressure at some point. Therefore, why not just go for the simple and strong developing move? }
5... c5 6. c3 cxd4 7. cxd4 dxe4 8. Nxe4
{ White has an excellent version of a standard IQP position, as Black's development is a bit awkward. }
8... Nd5 9. O-O Be7 10. Nc3
{ 'White has almost completed his development, so it is high time he shattered Black's position in the centre' writes Yevseev. }
10... N7f6
{ 10...O-O  11.Nxd5  exd5  12.Bf4  leaves White with an enduring plus,   while  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  is also better for White, who will have good attacking chances in the resulting semi-hanging pawns position. }
11. Bb5+
{ I recommended  11.Ne5  in the original repertoire, borrowing from Yevseev's analysis, but I'm no longer convinced that the resulting IQP position is particularly special for White. After  ...Bd7-c6  , Black manages to arrange his pieces quite harmoniously, and he shouldn't be too much worse. The text aims for a more concrete concession. }
11... Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Ne5 Qd6 14. Qa4+
{ This is the point of White's play - White is trying to make Black move his King. }
14... Kf8
{ 14...Nd7  15.Nb5  followed by  Nxd7  should also be a bit better for White. }
15. Re1
{ While Black is playing, e.g., ...h6, ...Kg8 and ...Kh7, White can activate his pieces and try to cause Black problems, e.g. on the open c-file, or with Nb5/Qb5 etc.. }
