1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nd7
{ Another move that doesn't have much significance aside from transpositional. Committing the Knight to the d7 square so early is a bit strange, especially since developing this piece to c6, where it puts pressure on d4 is so natural. }
4. Ngf3
{ 4.e5!?  is also kind of interesting, when  4...c5  5.c3  Ne7  6.Bd3  Nc6  is a perhaps slightly unexpected transposition to the  3...Nf6  main line.   Now Black's two options are really  4.Ngf3  Ne7  , transposing to the  ...Ne7  and  ...Nd7  variation, and  4...dxe4  5  Nxe4  , transposing to the main line of the French Rubinstein. }
4... Ne7
{ 4...dxe4  is the other main option, transposing into the French Rubinstein, although I would then wonder why Black didn't take on  e4  on move  3. }
5. Bd3
{ This position is covered via the move order  3...Ne7 4.Ngf3 Nd7 5.Bd3. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3rd Move Sidelines "]
[Black "3...h6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 h6
{ This move has been seen even less in practice than  3...a6  , but the idea is more or less the same.  Black essentially makes a half useful waiting move, so he can react to whatever information White provides him on his next turn.   4.Ngf3  Nf6!  exploits the fact that after  5.e5  White can no longer opt for the 'ideal' Ne2/Nf3 set-up.  4.Bd3  c5!  exploits the slight misplacement of the Bishop on  d3  for the resulting structure. Not that either of these are bad for White, but that's the basic idea.  In fact, the lines I gave in the initial repertoire are arguably not so convincing, while at the same time being rather sharp. }
4. c3 c5 5. exd5 Qxd5
{ After  5...exd5  , play will probably proceed along the lines of the  3...c5  1 chapter. For example, after  6.Ngf3  ,  6...Nf6  will be met by  7.Bb5+  , and  6.Ngf3  Nc6  by  7.Bb5  , waiting for Black to move his  f8  Bishop before taking on  c5  .   See the variations starting with this one for more info }
6. Ngf3 cxd4 7. Nxd4
{ In this case, the pawn on c3 helps White out, as in the normal ...Qxd5 variations, he has to play Bc4, O-O and Nb3 before finally being able to regain the pawn. Bc4 is still in the air, while Nb5, creating an awkward threat on c7, is also in play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3rd Move Sidelines "]
[Black "3...a6 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 a6
{ This is a high-class waiting move. Black makes a half-useful move while waiting for White to commit to a set-up, so he can then use that information to work out how best to reply. It's an interesting concept, but it hasn't fully caught on at the highest level, despite some very strong players trying it out occasionally. This move has been more popular than  3...h6  . }
4. Bd3
{ This is my new recommendation. I still think 4  Ngf3  is a good move, but after  4...Nf6!?  , White might have to go in for messy complications to get an advantage, as my suggestion of  5.e5  Nfd7  6.c4  can probably be neutralized by  6...c5!  (which I didn't mention)  (. The point of the text move is to retain the option of setting up the Knights harmoniously with Ng1-e2 and Nd2-f3 should Black play 4...Nf6.) }
4... c5 5. dxc5 Bxc5 6. Ngf3 Nf6 7. O-O dxe4
{ Simplying everything fails to solve Black's problems. } 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. Bxe4
Qxd1 10. Rxd1
{ White is actually even better than it may seem on first sight. The problem is that the Queenside is very difficult for Black to develop. ...Nc6 allows White to split his pawns with Bxc6, which should leave him with a depressing endgame task. Meanwhile, ...Nd7-f6 isn't a perfect solution either, as White can react by moving his Knight away from f3, then putting his Bishop there, making sure it's not easy for Black to develop his c8 Bishop. }
*

