4... c5 5. dxc5 Bxc5 6. Ngf3 Nf6 7. O-O O-O
{ 7...Nc6  transposes to  6...Nc6 7.O-O Nf6; starting here.  (The text probably just castles too quickly. The key is to react to what Black does with his King. If he delays castling, exd5 can make the e-file an annoyance for him. If he does castle, then e4-e5 makes sense, with the Bishop aiming at h7.) }
8. e5 Nfd7 9. Nb3 Be7 10. Qe2
{ I think White has a good version of these typical positions, because Black often waits to castle, to avoid coming under a quick Kingside attack. }
