{ Black has to maintain control over d4, because  10...Bd6  11.Nbd4  would be quite bad. }
11. Be3
{ We saw this in the 3...c5 variation as well. In this IQP position, when Black meets Nb3 with ...Bb6, the right plan is to challenge that Bishop's diagonal with Re1 and Be3. In this case, we even already had our Rook on e1. The Bishop on e6 is inconveniently placed, because if and when White plays Nc5 or N@@StartBracket@@b/f@@EndBracket@@d4, Black will have to seriously consider whether we might just take it. }
