{ Chigaev seems to have a thing for this line, so I figured I should include at least one of his games! }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. c3 c5 6. f4 Nc6 7. Ngf3 Qb6 8. Nb3
cxd4 9. cxd4 f6 10. Bd3
{ 10.Bd2  ±  Not the most natural move in the world, but d4 is safe for the time being, and this prevents the upcoming check from b4.   10.Be3  fxe5  11.fxe5  Ndxe5  12.Nxe5  Nxe5  13.Bd2  Nf7  14.Bd3  gives White decent compensation, but you can see why he didn't want to go for this. }
10... a5 11. a4 Bb4+ 12. Ke2
{ and not   12.Kf2 ?!  fxe5  13.fxe5  Ndxe5  14.Nxe5  Nxe5  15.Qh5+  g6 !!  16.Qxe5  O-O+  17.Ke2  Bd6  18.Qg5  Qxb3  19.Bxg6  hxg6  20.Qxg6+  when White only draws. }
12... Nf8
{ Intending ...Bd7 and ...0-0-0, but this seems to be a faulty plan.   12...O-O  13.Qc2  h6  14.Rf1  +=  doesn't look terribly appealing for Black, to be fair. }
13. Be3 Bd7 14. h4
{ A nice space gain, which also serves the purpose of discouraging ...Ng6. }
14... O-O-O { 14...h5  may tempt White to target the g7 pawn with  15.Rh3 !? }
15. h5 Be7 16. Kf2 Kb8 17. Bb5
{ Black has very little counterplay, and White just dominates the board. }
17... Nb4 18. Qe2 Rc8 19. Nc5
{ Note the use of the weaknened Queenside squares b5 and c5. } 19... Bc6 20.
Rhc1 Qd8 21. exf6
{ Arguably this isn't necessary, and it does create some potential avenues of counterplay for Black. It all turns out well for White in the game, though. }
21... gxf6 22. Bd2 Bxc5 23. dxc5
{ An interesting choice, which does nice things such as free up d4 for the Knight.   23.Rxc5  keeps the c-file as a line of attack. }
23... Rg8 24. Bxb4 axb4 25. a5 Bxb5
{ This allows White's Queen into b5, from where it can pick up the b4 pawn, and also participate in an attack against Black's King.   25...e5  26.Bxc6  Rxc6  is still somewhat unclear. }
26. Qxb5 Qd7 27. Qxb4 e5 28. a6 Ne6 29. fxe5 d4 30. Qxb7+ Qxb7 31. axb7 Kxb7
32. c6+ Kb6 33. Ra4 Kb5 34. Ra7 Rxc6 35. Rxc6 Kxc6 36. Ra6+ Kd7 37. exf6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Annotated Games "]
[Black "Chirila-Danin, Prague 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Ngf3 a5 8. a4
{ 8.Be2  was my repertoire recommendation.  See the variations starting here }
8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Bb4 10. Kf2
{ The reason why I don't like this 8.a4 line so much for White is that with Black not having played ...Qb6, he has almost saved a tempo in some weird sense. We saw lines where Black played ...Qb6 and then ...Qd8 in order to clear the way for ...Nb6-c4. Alternatively, Black can use the tempo he's 'saved' to create action in the centre faster. The computer hates this King move at first, but it also seems like the only way to complete development sensibly. Black is pretty much threatening ...Qb6, which, with no Nb3 available, might just win the d4 pawn.   10.Bd3 ??  Qb6  ∓  is just horrendous for White with no Nb3 available.   10.Qb3  is what the computer wants to play. Looks a bit odd to me, but fair enough. }
10... f6 { Naturally, Black wants to break open the centre ASAP. } 11. Nb3
{ This is what White unpinned himself to play. } 11... O-O 12. g3 Qb6
{ This spoils Black's previous idea! Black should dispense with this ...Qb6 move, especially considering White was just getting ready to remove his King from that diagonal.   12...fxe5  13.fxe5  Ndxe5 !?  14.dxe5  Nxe5  =∞  is interesting.   12...Nb6  ∞  looks like a good idea, making use of the fact that he did not play ... Qb6. }
13. Kg2 Be7 14. Bd3 { Now, it's business as usual for White. } 14... Nb4 15.
Bb1
{ The computer wants   15.Bb5 !  although I can certainly see why White wanted to leave his Bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal. }
15... Nb8
{ I understand Black's idea is to reroute the Knight to c6, but now is a bad time to take this piece away from the defense of the Kingside. Chirila takes his opportunity to exploit this.   15...Qc6  16.h4  Nb6 ?  17.Ng5 !  and wins. }
16. exf6 gxf6
{ Not the recapture Black probably wants to make, but this does at least keep the g5 square covered.   16...Bxf6  17.h4  +-  With no Knight to cover h7, this is going to be an extremely strong attack for White. }
17. f5 N8c6 18. Nh4 { This heralds a lethal Kingside attack. } 18... Rf7 19.
Bh6 e5 20. Qg4+ { All of White's pieces come flooding in. } 20... Kh8 21. Qh5
Kg8 22. Qg4+ { Harmlessly repeating the position once. } 22... Kh8 23. Qh5 Kg8
24. Ng6 Nd8 { 24...hxg6 ??  25.Qxg6+  Kh8  26.Qxf7  with mate to folow. } 25.
dxe5 fxe5 26. Nxe7+ Rxe7 27. f6 Rf7 28. Qg5+ Kh8 29. Bg7+ Kg8 30. Bxh7+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Annotated Games "]
[Black "mn (2126)-SS (2010), Ottawa 2017 "]
[Result "*"]

{ This game features a line outside of the repertoire suggested in this course. I'm showing it just in case you're interested in 5.Bd3, and also because the structure is relevant for the Guimard Variation. Also, because I wanted to include more of my games. Just being honest. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Bd3
{ Chess is a strange game sometimes. Obviously, you have no control over what openings your opponents will play. Lots of people complain that they spend hours studying a certain opening before a tournament, and then suddenly nobody plays into that opening against you anymore. At one point, I experienced the opposite effect. While I was writing my 'Fighting the French' course for Chessable, not once but twice in one tournament one of the main lines of the French Tarrasch appeared on my board. Not only that, but they both followed the same path for 14 moves @@StartBracket@@well, Black deviated on move fourteen...@@EndBracket@@.   5.f4  is my recommendation for this course. See this chapter for details }
5... c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Ne2 cxd4
{ Later that year, I had a game that went   7...f6 ?!  when  8.Nf4 !  is strong. }
8. cxd4 f6 9. exf6 Nxf6 10. Nf3
{ This is the most positionally circumspect arrangement of these Knights. }
10... Bd6 11. O-O Qc7
{ 11...0-0 is the other main line, while 11...Qb6 is played as well. With the text, Black prevents the strategically undesirable @@StartBracket@@for him@@EndBracket@@ exchange of Dark Squared Bishops which follows Bf4. However, the Queen can be somewhat misplaced on c7. }
12. h3
{ This little move was one of the main things I learned about while working on the initial course. It scores fantastically, is relatively fresh, and should promise White a fairly stable positional advantage. The idea is quite simple: White wants to develop with Be3, Re1, Rc1 and Nc3, but doesn't want to allow ...Ng4 in reply to Be3. }
12... O-O 13. Be3 Bd7 14. Re1
{ There's some subtleties involved here; moving this Rook first discourages the typical maneuvre ...Be8-h5, as after Ng5, the e6 pawn is slightly uncomfortable to defend. With the action taking place along the e-file in this case, having the Rook on e1 turns out to be more useful than having the Rook on c1. White is likely to play both moves anyway, but it makes sense to start with the text. Of course, I'm not nearly clever enough to work this out Over the Board, but I was still just parroting what I had learned at home. }
14... Be8
{ The other game went   14...Rae8  15.Rc1  Qb8  16.Nc3  Re7  17.a3  Be8  18.Nb5  Bf4  19.Qd2  Ne4  20.Bxe4  dxe4  21.Ng5  Bxe3  22.Qxe3  Na5  23.Qxe4  Rf5  24.Qxf5  exf5  25.Rxe7  Nc6  26.Re6  a6  27.Rce1  Bd7  28.Nd6  Bxe6  29.Rxe6  h6  30.Re8+  Qxe8  31.Nxe8  hxg5  32.d5  Nd8  33.Nd6  g6  34.g4  Kg7  35.gxf5  gxf5  36.Nxf5+  Kf6  37.Ne3  Ke5  38.Kg2  b5  39.Kf3  a5  40.Kg4  Nf7  41.Kh5  b4  42.Kg6  Nd6  43.Kxg5  Ne4+  44.Kg6  Nxf2  45.h4  Nd3  46.h5  Nf4+  47.Kg5  Ke4  48.h6  Kxe3  49.h7  Nxd5  50.h8=Q  Kd3  51.Qc8  Kd4  52.Qc6  1-0 mn @@StartBracket@@2126@@EndBracket@@ - ZD @@StartBracket@@2099@@EndBracket@@, 2017. }
15. Ng5 Bf7 16. Rc1
{ There's not really any reason to take the Bishop right away. I was still 'in book' at this point. }
16... h6
{ Forcing the exchange on f7 whilst weakening the Light Squares a little bit seems odd, but the alternative, going ...Kh8 intending ...Bg8, doesn't seem altogether appealing either.   16...Kh8  17.a3  Bg8  18.b4  a6  19.g3  h6  20.Nf4  ±  Navara-Michiels 2015 }
17. Nxf7 Qxf7 18. a3
{ I have written in my notes here 'Nothing terribly exciting so far. White's got a small plus; Bishop pair, blah, blah. Here's where the fun starts. ' Pretty eloquent stuff. }
18... e5
{ Black is voluntarily isolated his d-pawn in a bid for activity. Probably not a great decision objectively, but it was wonderful in practice, as it led to a complete mess. }
19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. Bb1
{ Positionally speaking, White must be extremely well off; Bishop pair, facing the isolani, as well as some Kingside Light Square weaknesses. Black does have some play though... }
20... Rad8 { At this point, I noticed there was a pawn hanging. } 21. Bxa7
{ This actually is a good move, although I played it based on a miscalculation. I'd seen the line 21...Ne4 22 Rf1 Nf3+ and decided White was winning. I was winning in every line I looked at...but Black draws in the line I missed - 24.. .Qh5! }
21... Ne4 22. Rf1
{ 22.f4 !  The move I played is okay as well, but it gets needlessly complicated. This suggestion by the computer shuts down Black's play down the f-file and b8-h2 diagonal.  22...Ng6   22...Nf3+ ?  23.gxf3  Qg6+  24.Kh1  Qf5  25.Bxe4  dxe4  26.Qb3+   22...Nc6  23.Be3  ±  23.g3  ± }
22... Nf3+ { wheee } 23. gxf3 Qg6+
{ 23...Ng5 ?!  An interesting try, which we discussed at length in the post mortem. We concluded White was winning based on the following:  24.f4 !  Attacking the Knight, and importantly, allowing the defensive Rc3 lift.  24...Bxf4   24...Qh5  This rather blunt try doesn't manage to give mate on h2.  25.fxg5  Qxh3  26.Qxd5+  This 'check and back' thing is a big help for White in defending himself.  26...Rf7  27.Qg2  +-   24...Nf3+  25.Kg2  Nh4+  26.Kh1 !  Evading the Knight checks.   24...Nxh3+  25.Kg2  Qh5  Tempting, but...   25...Nxf4+  26.Nxf4  Bxf4  27.Be3  +-  26.Rc3  +-  Saving the day again.  25.Rc3  +-  The key defensive Rook lift! We looked at this for a while, without finding anything for Black.   23...Qxf3 ?  24.Qxd5+  Rf7   24...Kh8  25.Qxe4  +-  25.Qxe4  +-   23...Qf5 ?  24.fxe4  Qxh3  25.Qxd5+  Kh8  26.e5  +-   23...Qh5 ?  24.fxe4 }
24. Kh1
{ 24.Ng3 !!  This is a better move than 24 Kh1 actually - I actually did see calculate this more or less accurately - however, since I'd missed 24 Kh1 Qh5, I was still convinced just moving the King was winning for me.  24...Bxg3   24...Nxg3  25.Bxg6  25.fxe4 !  Bxf2+  26.Kh1  Bxa7  27.exd5  +=  extra pawn! As far as I can tell, Black can't make any serious threats to White's open King in this fairly simplified position. However, he should of course be able to hold a draw with a bit of work. }
24... Rxf3
{ 24...Qh5 =  I'd missed this back when I took on a7. At first it looks like Black's winning @@StartBracket@@25 Ng1 Qe5 - mate?@@EndBracket@@, but actually it leads to a perpetual in one of two ways.  25.f4   25.Ng1  Qe5  26.f4  Qxf4  27.Nf3  Qf5 !   27...Qxf3+  28.Qxf3  Rxf3  29.Kg2  Rdf8  30.Ba2  +=  28.Ng1   28.Kg2  Qg6+  29.Kh1  Qf5  Qf4  Qxh3+  26.Kg1  Rxf4  27.Qxd5+   27.Nxf4 ??  Bxf4  -+  Rf7 }
25. Ng1
{ This Knight saves the day. Although, as it turns out, White can even get away with taking on d5 first, although I hadn't really considered this. @@StartBracket@@I just wanted to make it out alive with my extra piece!@@EndBracket@@   25.Qxd5+ !  Kh8  26.Ng1  +- }
25... Rf5
{ 25...Ng3+ !?  26.Kg2  +-  Not technically best, but this move is fun. Black has three pieces hanging and no good discoveries.   26.fxg3 !  Simply winning.  26...Qxg3  27.Qxd5+  Kh8  28.Qd2  +- }
26. Be3 Rdf8 27. Bxe4 dxe4 28. Qg4 Qf6 29. Qxe4 Bb8 30. Qxb7 Qe5 31. Qg2 R8f6
32. Rc5 Rg6 33. Rxe5 Rxg2 34. Re8+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Annotated Games "]
[Black "mn (2218)-JB (2270), Hamilton 2019 "]
[Result "*"]

{ To reiterate, the pawn structure in this game tends to be relevant for French Tarrasch players, even if you don't want to enter this specific line. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Bd3
{ 5.f4  is my recommendation for this course. See this chapter for details }
5... c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Ne2 cxd4 8. cxd4 f6
{ I had another game in 2019 that went   8...Be7 ?!  9.Nf3  f6  10.Nf4 ?!  Nf8 ?   10...Ndxe5 !  11.dxe5  fxe5  11.exf6  gxf6 ?!  12.O-O  Bd7  13.Ng5 !  This is similar to an idea which we saw in the Guimard Variation.  13...h5  14.Be2  and 1-0 @@StartBracket@@20@@EndBracket@@ in mn @@StartBracket@@2220@@EndBracket@@ - DS @@StartBracket@@2204@@EndBracket@@.  The spectacular   14.Bh7 !!  may be even stronger. }
9. exf6 Qxf6 10. Nf3 h6
{ Stopping Bg5 @@StartBracket@@and the subsequent Bh4-g3 maneuver@@EndBracket@@. }
11. O-O
{ I remembered that I'd recommended   11.Qc2 !?  in my first course, but for some reason I decided to deviate from it. It didn't go so well, because I really was only very vaguely familiar with the main line of this system. }
11... Bd6 12. Nc3
{ This is already a bit iffy. I think I'd gotten my lines mixed up. When Black's Queen is on f6, this Knight should really be going to g3, to assist with matters on the Kingside. }
12... O-O 13. Be3 Rd8
{ Preparing ...Nf8 followed by ...Bd7. The computer initially isn't too thrilled with this plan, but it's far and away the most common way Black has played this position in practice. }
14. Rc1 Nf8 15. Na4
{ I was trying to make some sense of my Knight being on c3. Ne2-c3-a4-c5 is a standard theme in the French Tarrasch, but not so much when Black's pieces are gathering around the White King so quickly.   15.h3 !?  My computer seems to really like the plan of h3, Nh2 and Ng4. Interesting idea for sure. }
15... e5
{ Possibly not a great decision objectively, but it worked wonders in practice.Especially with White's Knight sitting on a4 @@StartBracket@@which was hanging in a surprising amount of lines that I calculated@@EndBracket@@, breaking open the centre and putting pressure on White seems like a good idea. He does, however, acquiesce to taking on an IQP.   15...Ng6  with counterplay. }
16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Be2
{ Thinking I'd already messed up and was in some trouble, I went for this clearly not very ambitious move. At least once Black takes on f3 and I recapture, my Bishop is aimed at the isolated d5 pawn.   17.Nxe5  Qxe5  18.g3  ±  I was extremely uneasy playing this, but the computer sees no problems and gives White a clear plus. }
17... Nxf3+ { 17...Ne6 !?  is also interesting. } 18. Bxf3 d4
{ 18...Ne6 !?  may be even stronger. } 19. Bxd4 Bxh2+ 20. Kxh2 Rxd4 21. Qb3+
Be6 { 21...Kh8  22.Bxb7   22.Nc5  +=  Bxb7  23.Qxb7  Qf4+  24.g3  Rb8  ∞ } 22.
Qxb7
{ White has picked up a pawn, but my King is unsafe and Black is quite active. There's also the matter of probably having to spend a move removing the Knight from the undesirable a4 square. }
22... Rad8 23. Nc3 Ng6
{ 23...Nh7  =∞  with the idea of ...Ng5 may be dangerous. } 24. Rcd1
{ This certainly looks like the first step towards consolidating. } 24... Ne5
25. Rxd4
{ 25.Be2  would be more ambitious, avoiding the endgame that would occur if Black takes on f3. I think I was still in turtle mode after grabbing the pawn on b2, though. }
25... Rxd4 26. Re1 Nd3
{ Black continues to try to play for an attack in the middlegame, but would probably be best served by bailing out into the endgame, which should be fine for him.   26...Nxf3+  27.Qxf3  Qxf3  28.gxf3  Kf7 = }
27. Re2 Rh4+ 28. Kg1 Qf4 29. Qa8+ Kh7 30. Qe4+
{ 30.Rxe6  Rh1+ !  31.Kxh1  Qh4+  32.Kg1  Qxf2+  draws by perpetual. } 30...
Bf5 31. Qxf4 Rxf4 32. Nd5 Rd4 33. Rd2 Kh8 34. Ne7 Bh7 35. Be2 { Blech! } 35...
Nf4 { or   35...Nc1  -+ } 36. Rxd4 Nxe2+ 37. Kf1 Nxd4 38. Ke1 Be4 39. f3 Bb7
40. Kd2 g5 41. Kd3 Ne6 42. Ke3 Nf4 43. g3 Nd5+ *

