1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6
{ This is a somewhat strange sideline which we briefly discussed in the 3...dxe4 chapter. I suppose I understand it if Black wants to recapture with the g-pawn, but if his intention is to take back with a piece, he should definitely start with   4...Nd7 }
5. Nxf6+ Qxf6 6. Nf3 h6 { Black already has to take a time-out to stop Bg5. }
7. Bd3 c5
{ Here Black falls afoul of the basic principle where you shouldn't offer to open the position when behind in development.   7...Bd6  8.Qe2  ± }
8. Be3 { Here's where we left off in the theoretical chapters. } 8... Nd7 9.
O-O
{ According to the computer I'm not being ambitious enough here.   9.Qe2  +-  followed by long castling, with h4 and g4 in mind, is fantastic for White. Black's Queen is definitely a target for Kingside pawn advances, and retreating to d8 doesn't especially inspire either. }
9... a6 { 9...Bd6  should really be played here. } 10. Re1 Bd6 11. c3 O-O 12.
Bc2
{ Planning Qd3. The fact that there's a Queen on f6 and not a Knight doesn't do Black any favours for his King safety. He now seeks to rectify this. }
12... Qe7
{ Although, the Knight is somewhat vulnerable on f6.   12...Rd8  13.Qd3  Nf8  14.Rad1  ±  With a Knight on f8, there's no mate, although White is still quite a bit better. }
13. Qd3 Nf6 14. Ne5 { With the idea of Ng4. } 14... Rd8 15. Ng4 b6 16. Nxh6+
{ Completely unnecessary and also just a bad move.   16.Nxf6+  Qxf6  17.Qh7+  Kf8  18.Rad1  +-  isn't mate yet, but with d5 or dxc5 coming up, White is doing fantastically. }
16... gxh6
{ Returning the favour, and everything makes sense again.   16...Kf8  ∞  would've raised serious questions about what White is doing with his Knight, which is stuck on h6, while Black runs his King into the centre. }
17. Bxh6 Bxh2+
{ An attempt.   17...cxd4  18.f4  +-  and Black doesn't have a terribly good defense to the Queen swinging over to the Kingside. }
18. Kxh2 Ng4+ 19. Kg1 f5 { 19...Nxh6  20.Qh7+  Kf8  21.Qxh6+  +- } 20. Bf4
{ with an extra pawn and a continuing attack. } 20... Qf6 21. Qg3 Kf7 22. f3
Nh6 23. Be5 Qg6 24. Qxg6+ Kxg6 25. Bc7 Rg8 26. Bxb6 cxd4 27. Bxd4 Rb8 28. b4
Kf7 29. Kf2 Bb7 30. Rh1 Rg6 31. Rh2 Rbg8 32. Rah1 Ke7 33. Rxh6 Rxg2+ 34. Ke3
Rxc2 35. Rh7+ *

