[White "Annotated Games "]
[Black "Shirov-Chernin, Groningen 1993"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7
{ Chernin, known for writing a good book on the Pirc, plays what might be the antithesis of the Pirc Defense here. }
5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Ng3 Be7 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 c6
12. c4
{ Here's where we left off. White has two Bishops, more space and a pleasant position. I assume the intention was to acquire a rock solid position that Shirov wouldn't be able to do much against. That being said, I imagine Shirov was pretty happy to have two Bishops menacingly pointing towards his opponent's King. }
12... Re8 13. Rfe1 Bf8 14. Rad1 Qa5 15. Bb1
{ Just on principle, it makes a lot of sense to bring both Rooks to the middle and optimize your pieces before beginning to break in the centre or make moves on the Kingside. }
15... g6 { Swinging the Bishop to g7 to try to neutralize the one on b2. } 16.
h4
{ This makes a lot of sense as a reaction to Black's last move, as the first player has been provided with a bit of a hook. }
16... Bg7
{ 16...h5 !?  Maybe this is best. It's a pretty scary move to make, but it feels like at some point Black should be doing something to try to forestall White's Kingside progress. Maybe g4 will end up being useful for a Knight. Let's be real, though, the only reason I'm saying this is because my computer flags it up as a good option. }
17. Bc3
{ White has to kick the Queen off the fifth rank before playing h5, as that square is currently guarded thrice. }
17... Qc7 18. h5 b5 19. h6
{ This turns out to be a bit hasty. In general, this is a very desirable advance for White. Shirov understood this in 1993, and in 2020, in the time of Alpha/Leela Zero, we arguably understand this even better. That being said, Black can currently take this pawn. Even though he has to give up a piece to do so, Black gets three pawns and the counterplay he's been so craving. }
19... Bxh6
{ 19...Bh8 ??  20.Ne4  +-  is too timid and just horrendous for Black. } 20. d5
{ This was White's point; uncovering an attack on the Knight on f6 while threatening all sorts of other unpleasantries. }
20... cxd5 { There's not really any sense in turning back at this point. } 21.
Bxf6 bxc4
{ This is a decision, computers aside, I honestly just don't understand. Why not snip off the powerful Bishop on f6 before taking on c4? I'm sure Mr. Chernin, a far far stronger player than I'll ever be, had his reasons, but this looks like a clear mistake to me.   21...Nxf6  22.Qxf6  bxc4  ∞ }
22. Bb2 { The Bishop lives on, and so does White's initiative. } 22... cxb3 23.
Nh5
{ I suppose this is what Chernin missed. It's a brilliant move and it stems from the power of the two Bishops. }
23... f5 { 23...gxh5  24.Qxh5  Qf4  25.Rd4  +- } 24. Rxd5
{ Woohoo! The only reason I'm not going to give this an exclam or two is because my computer claims there's a better move.   24.Bxf5 !!  Does it get any better than this? Probably not by much.  24...gxf5  25.Rxd5  +- }
24... gxh5 { 24...exd5 ?  25.Qxd5+  Kf8  26.Ba3+  +-  sees Black get sniped. }
25. Rxf5
{ Not since Steinitz-von Bardeleben have I seen a Rook this determined to get captured. }
25... Nf8 26. Rxh5 bxa2 27. Bxa2 Bg7 28. Qg4 Kh8 29. Bxg7+ Qxg7 30. Rg5 Ng6 31.
Bb1 Qc3 32. Rd1 Qf6 33. Rd7 Re7 34. Rxe7 Qxe7 35. Bxg6 Rg8 36. Qd4+ Rg7 37. Rh5
e5 *

