{ Michael Adams is one of my favourite players  (in spite of the fact that someone once told me 'I've never heard anyone say Michael Adams was their favourite player')  . He conducts this game beautifully. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8.
O-O Ne7 9. Nb3 Bd6 10. Re1 O-O 11. Bd3 h6 12. h3 Nf5 13. c3 Qf6 14. Bc2 Rd8 15.
Qd3 g6 16. Qd2
{ I'm no longer really sure if this is strictly the best move, but it's got an element of beauty to it. With Qd3, White made a threat on h7, which was met by ...g6, which in turn weakened the h6 pawn. Therefore, Adams immediately switches his Queen to the relevant diagonal.   16.Bd2  += is my suggestion in the trainable section. }
16... Bf8 17. Qf4
{ Black defended h6, but undefended f4, and the Queen immediately hops in. Sure, it's not a cascade of sacrifices, but I find this kind of thing really beautiful. }
17... Bg7 18. Bd2
{ 18.g4  g5  19.Qh2  Nfe7  20.Qg2  +=  showcases a similar idea to one we'll see in a second, albeit in a less spectacular way. }
18... g5 19. Qh2
{ 19.Qa4 ?  seems 'forced', but Black has an excellent game after  19...Nd6  =+ }
19... b6
{ Not the most critical, and unfortunately, it doesn't allow White to show his idea.   19...Bf8  20.Rad1  Bd6  chases the Queen to h1.  21.Qh1  +=  Turns out, the Queen doesn't mind being on h1 at all, as after g2-g4, it both keeps the King safe and influences the long diagonal, where the key d5 pawn is located. This shows a level of understanding that I think very very few people in the world have. }
20. Rad1 Ba6 21. Bxf5
{ With this capture no longer being met by ...Bxf5, developing a new piece while recapturing, Adams decides  that it is time to play it. White trades off his only minor piece that cannot influence d4 directly for a minor piece which was very much doing so. }
21... Qxf5 22. Be3 Bc4 23. Nbd4 Bxd4
{ This seems pretty risky, because just optically it leaves Black's King looking quite airy. That being said, it's hard to imagine that Yusupov expected his King to come under attack quite as rapidly as it in fact does. }
24. Nxd4 Nxd4 25. Bxd4 Re8 26. Qc7
{ And suddenly the Queen swoops in from its hiding place on h2. } 26... Bxa2
{ This is an extremely risky pawn to grab, although I expect Yusupov is just storing nuts for the upcoming winter, to use a phrase that I literally just made up five seconds ago.   26...Be2 !? }
27. Qc6
{ Everything is hanging. And by 'everything', I mean specifically the Rook on e8 and the pawn on h6. Trading Rooks doesn't help Black, because then its the one on a8 being hung out to dry. Pun very much intended. }
27... Rf8 28. Qxh6 f6 29. Re7 Rf7 30. Rde1 Raf8 31. Rxf7 Kxf7 32. g4 *

