{ Here's a game where I got a comfortable enough position against a GM before completely self-destructing. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nf6 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
8. O-O Be7 9. dxc5 Nxc5
{ You may be surprised to see this line played by a guy who outrates his opponent by about 400 points and roughly 4 classes of title, but this is kinda just what this guy is known for doing. He gets positions like this, and just kinda outplays you. }
10. Nb3
{ This is fine, although I was mixing up my move orders, as in the first version of this repertoire I instead recommended  10.Nd4  Qd7  and only now  11.N2b3     My current recommendation is  10.Nd4  Qd7  11.N2f3  , see here }
10... Nce4 11. Nfd4 Qd7 12. f3 Nd6 13. Nc5 Qc8 14. Nd3 O-O 15. c3
{ I'd already spent more time than I should've reaching this position.   15.Re1  is what I recommended both in the first version of this repertoire, and the present one. }
15... Re8 16. Re1 Bf8 17. Bg5
{ 17.Rxe8  Nfxe8  18.Be3  +=  looks like a fairly stable advantage for White, due to the nice grip on d4. Notice that, importantly, ...Nc4 is not quite as annoying is it could be, given that the Knight on d3 is conveniently covering b2. }
17... Rxe1+ 18. Qxe1 Nd7 19. Be7
{ I guess this isn't bad per se, swapping off pieces when the opponent has an IQP. However, it does look a bit funny to trade off an active Bishop for one sitting on f8. }
19... Qc4 20. Bxf8 Nxf8 21. Ne5 Qc7 22. Qg3 Qb6 23. Qf2 Re8 24. Re1
{ This is a small mistake, in my opinion, simply because it allows Black to start prodding.   24.Nd3 }
24... Qa6 25. a3
{ Now, a slight weakness has been created, and I start to prefer Black ever so slightly. The d-pawn is blockaded, but it's in no danger. }
25... f6 26. Ng4 Rxe1+ 27. Qxe1 Qb6 28. Qg3
{ Objectively, this is a pretty bad move, because of 28...Nf5. The thing is, I thought I could pretty comfortably hold a draw in the resulting symmetrical ending, which would've been a pretty good result for me considering I was A@@EndBracket@@ already in time trouble and B@@EndBracket@@ being significantly outrated. I can't recommend this type of unambitious play, though. }
28... Kf7
{ A good practical decision, keeping everything on the board, even though objectively the endgame is ever so slightly favourable for Black.   28...Nf5  29.Qf4  Nxd4  30.Qxd4  Qxd4+  31.cxd4  Ne6  32.Ne3  Nxd4  33.Nxd5  Kf7  =+ }
29. Ne3 Nb5 30. Nef5 Ne6 31. Qf2 Nexd4 32. Nxd4 Nd6
{ The computer says Black is even slightly worse after this move, but again my opponent had absolutely no intention of letting me off the hook in a symmetrical structure. }
33. b3
{ Notice how none of my Queenside pawns are currently defending any of my other Queenside pawns. If you're keeping score at home, that's not good.   33.a4  += }
33... Qc5 34. Qe3 Qc8 35. Kf2 a6 36. Ke2 h5 37. Kd2
{ This is kind of just time trouble shuffling. I think I remember my metaphorical flag was basically falling at this point, and I was playing off the increment. How I managed to spend so much time in a simple-seeming position is another story altogether. The rest of this is just a travesty. You're welcome to play through it. I'd prefer it you didn't. But you can. }
37... b5 38. Qf4 Qd7 39. Qe3
{ 39.Qh4 !  wins for White, e.g.  39...g6  40.g4  +- } 39... a5 40. Qd3 a4 41.
bxa4 bxa4 42. Qh7 Nc4+ 43. Kc1 Qb7 44. Qxh5+ Ke7 45. Nf5+ Ke6 46. Nd4+ Kd6 *

