{ Here's a game that shows the strength of White's attack if Black isn't careful. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Ngf3 cxd4 6. Bc4 Qd7 7. O-O Nc6 8.
Nb3 a6 9. a4 Nf6 10. Qe2 Bd6 11. Rd1 e5 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 Qe7 14. Rxd6
Qxd6 15. b3 e4 16. Ba3 Qf4 17. Qe1 Be6 18. Qa5 Rc8
{ It feels a bit counter-intuitive that this move is so bad, as White was certainly hinting at Qc5 with his last move. However, my computer is already screaming a big plus at me, going back and forth between '+/-' and '+-'.  As discussed in the theoretical section,   18...Rd8 !  is pretty much the only move.  19.Re1  ∞   19.Ne5 ?  here can be met simply by  19...Nd7  ∓ }
19. Ne5
{ Both bringing the Knight into the attack, and cutting off the Queen from the defense. }
19... Ng4
{ Logical, as Black is trying both to swap off a set of pieces, and allow his Queen to participate in defense.   19...Nd7 ?!  doesn't work here due to the lack of coverage from a Rook sitting on d8, e.g.  20.Bxe6  fxe6  21.Nxd7  Kxd7  22.Rd1+  Ke8  23.Qb6  +-  with an ongoing attack. }
20. Nxg4
{ This is far from a bad move, but it's also not the most direct win.   20.Bb5+ !  axb5  21.Qxb5+  Rc6  22.Nxc6  Qxh2+  23.Kf1  Qh1+  24.Ke2  Qxa1 ?  25.Ne5+  Kd8  26.Qa5+  Kc8  27.Bd6  with mate coming up was shown in the trainable section. }
20... Qxg4
{ Taking the Queen away from the defense of the d6 square is a mistake, which White swiftly punishes.   20...Bxg4  21.Qd5  +-  is great for White, with ideas of Bd6, Rd1, Re1 and f3, but not quite as good as what White gets in the game.   21.Qb4  Rc7  22.Re1  is still promising for White, but not immediately winning. }
21. Qb4
{ Note that Black's Rook on c8 couldn't prevent White from accessing this diagonal altogether. }
21... Rc7
{ This covers both e7 and b7, but White still has a point of entry.   21...Qg5  22.Qxb7  +- }
22. Qd6 { This is why the Queen probably should've stayed on f4. } 22... Rd7
{ 22...Bxc4  23.Qxc7  Qd7  and now the simplest is probably just  24.Qxd7+  Kxd7  25.bxc4  +-  with an extra piece. }
23. Qb8+ Rd8 24. Qxb7
{ White's now just picking up all the Queenside pawns, with an ongoing attack, because it's basically impossible for Black's King to escape the danger zone. }
24... Rd7 25. Qc8+ Rd8 26. Qc6+ Rd7 27. Re1
{ White brings the last piece into the attack. } 27... h5 28. Bxa6 f6
{ Accpording to the computer this is relatively Black's best bet, but it does allow White to pick up significant material. }
29. Rxe4 Kf7 30. Rxg4 Rd1+ 31. Bf1 hxg4 32. f3 Rc8 33. Qe4 Re8 34. Qe2 Ra1 35.
Bb4 Rd8 36. fxg4 Rdd1 37. Kf2 Bd5 38. Qe7+ Kg6 39. Bd3+ *

